values
('sport-studies', '5-1-4-technology-to-enhance-spectatorship', '5.1.4 Technology to Enhance Spectatorship', '{"learn": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "What ''enhancing spectatorship'' means", "html": "<h4>The idea</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Spectatorship</strong> is the experience of <strong>watching</strong> sport — whether that''s live inside a stadium or arena, or watching on television, a stream or a phone.</li>\n<li>One role of technology in sport is to make that watching experience <strong>better</strong>: clearer, more exciting, and easier to follow.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Not the same as performance, safety or officiating</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>This is a separate role from technology that helps a performer play better, technology that keeps people safe, or technology that helps an official make a correct decision.</li>\n<li>Here, the audience is the <strong>spectator</strong>, not the player or the official — so ask \"does this make the watching experience better for the crowd or the viewer?\"</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Two settings to remember</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Inside the venue</strong> — fans in their seats at a stadium, arena or track.</li>\n<li><strong>Away from the venue</strong> — fans watching on TV, a stream, or checking an app.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "Which question best captures what ''technology to enhance spectatorship'' is about?", "options": ["Does this technology make the watching experience better for fans?", "Does this technology help a performer refine a competitive technique?", "Does this technology protect a participant''s body from serious injury?", "Does this technology help an official reach the correct decision?"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Spectatorship is about the audience''s experience of watching, not the performer''s technique, participant safety or officiating accuracy — those are separate roles of technology."}}, {"title": "Big screens and enhanced broadcast coverage", "html": "<h4>Big screens inside the stadium</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Large screens fitted inside stadia and arenas show <strong>action replays</strong> and <strong>slow-motion replays</strong> of key moments, so fans in the crowd can see incidents they may have missed live.</li>\n<li>When an official reviews a decision, the big screen can show fans the same replay the official is using, so the crowd can follow and understand an appeal rather than just waiting for an announcement.</li>\n<li>Example: at a cricket ground, the big screen might show a ball-tracking replay during a review, letting the crowd see why a batter was given out or not out.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Enhanced television broadcast coverage</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Broadcasters use <strong>multiple camera angles</strong> around a venue, so viewers at home can see an incident from several different views rather than one fixed angle.</li>\n<li><strong>On-screen graphics</strong> add extra information over the picture — such as a trajectory line, a split-time comparison, or a graphic showing how close a decision was — helping viewers understand what is happening.</li>\n<li>Example: an on-screen speed reading during a tennis serve, or an onboard camera view during a cycling or motorsport event, both add detail a viewer could not otherwise see.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "Why might a stadium show fans the same review replay on its big screen that an official is using?", "options": ["So the crowd can follow and understand the decision, not just wait for an announcement", "So the official watching from the touchline can see the incident for the very first time ever", "So players on the pitch can argue with the decision much more easily", "So the stadium can reduce the total number of match officials used"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Sharing the replay lets the watching crowd follow the same evidence as the official, turning a wait into part of the spectator experience — it isn''t there to help the official see it first, encourage arguing, or cut staff."}}, {"title": "Apps, live stats and applying examples correctly", "html": "<h4>Live stats and second-screen apps</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Fans can use official <strong>apps or websites</strong> during an event to check <strong>live statistics</strong> — such as a runner''s split times, a team''s possession percentage, or a player''s distance covered — while still watching the action.</li>\n<li>This adds detail the naked eye cannot supply, and lets a fan away from the venue feel closer to the event.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Always name a sport or setting</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Weak answer: <em>\"Technology helps spectators.\"</em> That names a role but gives no detail.</li>\n<li>Strong answer: <em>\"A big screen at a rugby stadium replays a disputed try in slow motion, so fans can see the evidence and understand the referee''s decision, instead of only hearing an announcement.\"</em></li>\n<li>The mark almost always needs a <strong>named example linked to a specific benefit</strong> — not just the word \"technology\".</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Don''t confuse this with the evaluation topic</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>This topic is about how technology is <strong>used</strong> to improve the spectator experience. A different topic asks you to <strong>weigh up</strong> the positives and negatives of technology for spectators — save that judgement for that topic, and focus here on explaining clear uses and benefits.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "A strong exam answer about enhancing spectatorship should always include...", "options": ["A named example of the technology linked to a specific benefit for fans", "The word ''technology'' repeated as many times as you possibly can manage", "A criticism of an official''s overall performance in the fixture", "A description of a performer''s personal training programme"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Naming the technology and linking it to a real benefit for the audience is what earns marks — repeating a word, criticising officials, or describing training is off-topic here."}}]}, "terms": {"enabled": true, "pairs": [{"term": "Spectatorship", "definition": "The experience of watching sport, live in a venue or through broadcast and apps"}, {"term": "Big screen", "definition": "In-stadium screen showing replays and review decisions to the crowd"}, {"term": "Broadcast graphics", "definition": "On-screen information, such as a speed reading, added to the TV picture"}, {"term": "Multiple camera angles", "definition": "Several broadcast views of the same incident shown to viewers"}, {"term": "Live-stats app", "definition": "App or website giving fans extra statistics during an event"}, {"term": "Slow-motion replay", "definition": "Footage played back at reduced speed so an incident can be studied clearly"}]}, "mcq": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "What does ''enhancing spectatorship'' mean in the context of technology in sport?", "options": ["Making the experience of watching sport better for the audience", "Making a performer''s competitive technique more accurate", "Making the playing surface much safer for participants", "Making it easier for an official to review a contested decision"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Spectatorship is about the watching experience; improving technique, surface safety and officiating accuracy are separate roles of technology in sport."}, {"question": "What is the main purpose of showing an action replay on a stadium''s big screen?", "options": ["To let the crowd see a key moment again and follow what happened", "To completely replace the need for any match officials working at the fixture", "To make the playing surface much more visible to the groundstaff", "To give performers a good deal of extra recovery time between events"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Big-screen replays are for the crowd''s benefit, not to remove officials, help groundstaff, or give performers recovery time."}, {"question": "A broadcaster adds an on-screen graphic showing a serve''s exact speed during a tennis match. This mainly helps...", "options": ["viewers at home understand more detail about what just happened", "the player serve the ball with much greater accuracy next time", "the official decide whether that particular serve was in or out", "the groundstaff prepare the court surface for the next game"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The graphic is broadcast information for the viewer''s understanding, not a tool for the player''s technique, the official''s decision, or court preparation."}, {"question": "Why might a fan use a live-stats app while watching a match on television?", "options": ["To see extra detail, such as player statistics, that the broadcast picture alone does not show", "To officially referee the match themselves from home using the app, fully replacing the real match officials", "To physically replace the stadium''s existing big-screen system", "To stop the broadcaster from showing any camera angles at all"], "answer": 0, "explain": "A stats app adds detail for the viewer''s own interest — it does not turn a fan into an official, replace stadium screens, or block camera angles."}, {"question": "Which of these is an example of technology enhancing spectatorship, rather than officiating?", "options": ["A big screen replaying a great goal in slow motion for the crowd to enjoy again", "A video review system overturning a refereeing decision out on the pitch itself", "A sensor confirming to the official whether a ball crossed the goal line correctly", "A system checking a serve landed correctly inside the line for the umpire"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Replaying a moment for the crowd''s enjoyment is about the spectator experience; the other three examples are about helping an official reach a correct decision."}, {"question": "A stadium adds giant screens purely so fans can watch replays and see review decisions explained. This is best described as technology used to...", "options": ["enhance the spectator experience", "enhance a performer''s competitive technique", "increase participant safety during the event", "support a governing body''s overall funding model"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Screens aimed at helping the crowd follow the action and decisions are enhancing spectatorship, not technique, safety, or funding."}]}, "fib": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"text": "Spectatorship means the experience of [watching] sport, whether live or on a screen."}, {"text": "A big screen inside a stadium can show fans an action [replay] so they can see a moment again."}, {"text": "Broadcasters add on-screen [graphics] to give viewers extra information, such as a speed reading."}, {"text": "Multiple camera [angles] let broadcast viewers see an incident from more than one view."}, {"text": "A live-stats [app] lets a fan check extra statistics, such as split times, during an event."}]}, "tf": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"statement": "Technology that enhances spectatorship is mainly about improving the watching experience for fans.", "answer": true, "explain": "That''s the definition — it is about the audience''s experience, whether in the stadium or watching remotely."}, {"statement": "A big screen replay in a stadium is mainly there to help a performer train more effectively.", "answer": false, "explain": "Big-screen replays are aimed at the crowd''s experience, not at training a performer."}, {"statement": "On-screen broadcast graphics, like a speed reading, can help viewers understand more detail about what happened.", "answer": true, "explain": "Graphics add information the naked eye could not supply, helping the audience follow the action."}, {"statement": "A live-stats app used by a fan at home is an example of technology enhancing officiating.", "answer": false, "explain": "A fan checking stats is about the spectator experience, not helping an official reach a decision."}, {"statement": "Multiple camera angles let broadcast viewers see an incident from more than one point of view.", "answer": true, "explain": "Different camera positions around a venue give viewers a fuller picture of the same moment."}, {"statement": "Showing a review replay on a stadium''s big screen always removes the need for a match official.", "answer": false, "explain": "The screen helps the crowd follow the decision — the official, not the screen, still makes the final call."}]}, "misc": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"myth": "If spectators can see it happening, it must be an example of technology enhancing spectatorship.", "truth": "The test is not whether spectators can SEE it — it''s whether the technology''s main purpose is to improve the watching experience. A goal-line sensor is visible to the crowd, but its purpose is helping the official make a correct call, so it belongs with officiating, not spectatorship. Ask: ''who is this mainly FOR — the crowd, or the official?''", "check": {"question": "A goal-line sensor confirms the ball crossed the line for the referee. Even though the crowd can see the outcome, this is best classed as...", "options": ["technology enhancing spectatorship", "technology supporting officiating", "technology enhancing performance", "technology increasing participant safety"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Its main purpose is giving the official correct information, so it belongs with officiating, even though the crowd can also see the result."}}, {"myth": "Naming ''big screens'' is enough to answer any question about enhancing spectatorship.", "truth": "Naming the technology is only the first step. The mark almost always needs the SPECIFIC benefit linked to it — what the screen actually shows, and why that helps fans. ''Big screens'' alone earns little; ''a big screen replays a disputed decision so the crowd can follow it'' earns the mark.", "check": {"question": "Which answer about big screens is most likely to earn full marks?", "options": ["Big screens exist inside most modern stadiums built all around the world today", "A big screen replays a review so the crowd can follow the decision", "Big screens are usually very large and extremely bright", "Some large stadiums have more than one big screen"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Only this option links the technology to a specific benefit for the audience — the others just describe the screen."}}, {"myth": "This topic is the same as weighing up the positives and negatives of technology for fans.", "truth": "This topic is about how technology is USED to enhance the experience — explaining benefits with named examples. Weighing up both the positives AND the negatives for spectators is a separate, later topic. Keep this topic focused on clear, positive uses.", "check": {"question": "A question on THIS topic mainly wants you to...", "options": ["explain positive uses of technology for spectators with examples", "list every possible negative effect on spectators in a great deal of detail", "describe a performer''s personal training schedule", "weigh up the costs and benefits of officiating technology only"], "answer": 0, "explain": "This topic focuses on explaining enhancement/uses with named examples; weighing positives and negatives together belongs to a separate topic."}}]}, "tips": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "Command words for this topic — what each one wants", "html": "<p>Questions on enhancing spectatorship are usually short recall or short explain. Match your answer length to the command word:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify / State</strong> — just name a piece of technology. \"Identify one way technology enhances spectatorship\" = one named example. 1 mark.</li>\n<li><strong>Describe</strong> — say what the technology does. \"Describe how big screens are used\" = explain what appears on the screen.</li>\n<li><strong>Explain</strong> — give a reason, using \"because\". \"Explain how this benefits spectators\" = the use PLUS why it helps the audience.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Read the mark tariff:</strong> [1] wants one point; [2] usually wants two points, or one point developed with a reason; [4] in Section B wants points applied to the scenario given.</p>", "check": {"question": "A question says: ''Identify one piece of technology that enhances spectatorship [1]''. What is the safest answer?", "options": ["One named example, such as a big screen replay", "A long paragraph describing several different technologies", "A description of how an official reviews a decision", "An explanation of a performer''s diet and training"], "answer": 0, "explain": "''Identify'' + [1] wants one named example — nothing about officiating, training or a lengthy paragraph is needed."}}, {"title": "The golden rule: name the technology AND the benefit", "html": "<p>The single most common way to lose marks here is naming the technology with no benefit attached. Build every answer as <strong>technology → what it shows/does → benefit for the fan</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>❌ 0–1 marks:</strong> \"Big screens.\"</li>\n<li><strong>✅ full marks:</strong> \"A big screen replays a disputed try in slow motion, so fans in the stadium can see the evidence and follow the referee''s decision.\"</li>\n</ul>\n<p>In <strong>Section B</strong> the question gives you a scenario (a named venue, a named event). Use a detail <em>from that scenario</em>, not a general example.</p>", "check": {"question": "In a Section B scenario about a named stadium, your example of enhancing spectatorship should come from...", "options": ["any technology you happen to have heard of before", "the scenario you are given", "a completely different sport entirely", "your own personal opinion of the stadium"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Section B is applied — marks come from using the scenario given, not a random unrelated example."}}, {"title": "Where this appears + sentence starters", "html": "<p><strong>Where it shows up:</strong> enhancing spectatorship appears as quick recall in <strong>Section A</strong> (identify/describe a technology), and as applied points in <strong>Section B</strong> scenarios about a venue or event upgrading its technology. It can also feed a <strong>Section C</strong> 8-mark discussion of how technology affects the wider spectator experience.</p>\n<p><strong>Three punchy tips:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Split your examples into \"inside the venue\" (big screens, replays) and \"away from the venue\" (broadcast graphics, apps) so you always have more than one type ready.</li>\n<li>Always name a sport or setting — a vague \"technology helps fans\" answer earns little.</li>\n<li>Keep this topic about uses and benefits; save weighing up downsides for the evaluation topic.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Sentence starters for a longer answer:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\"One example of technology enhancing spectatorship is… because…\"</li>\n<li>\"This benefits fans by…\"</li>\n<li>\"However, the same technology might not help every fan, because…\"</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "Splitting examples into ''inside the venue'' and ''away from the venue'' mainly helps because...", "options": ["it guarantees full marks on every single question you attempt", "it gives you more than one type of example ready to use", "it means you never need to give a named example", "it replaces the need to explain any benefit at all"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Having both types ready means you can answer whichever setting a question describes, with a specific example rather than a vague one."}}]}, "exam": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "Identify <strong>two</strong> examples of technology that enhance the spectator experience.", "marks": 2, "hint": "Just name two — pick from big screens/replays inside the stadium, or broadcast graphics/apps away from the venue.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 2 marks (AO1)</h5>\n<p><strong>1 mark for each valid example named, to a maximum of two. Accept any two different examples, including:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Big screen action replay / slow-motion replay</li>\n<li>On-screen broadcast graphics (e.g. a speed reading or trajectory line)</li>\n<li>Multiple camera angles</li>\n<li>Live-stats app or website</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Do not credit the same example written twice.</p>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Which of these is the best example of technology enhancing the spectator experience, rather than officiating?", "marks": 1, "hint": "Think about which option is mainly FOR the crowd''s enjoyment, not for helping an official decide.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — A big screen replaying a great save for the crowd to enjoy again.</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>This is mainly for the audience''s enjoyment and understanding of the moment.</li>\n<li>The other options are all mainly for helping an official reach a correct decision.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Explain how <strong>two</strong> of Redcliffe Arena''s changes enhance the spectator experience.", "marks": 4, "hint": "Take each change in turn. Say what it lets fans do, then why that improves their experience. Use details from the scenario (the screens above the court, and the app).", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 4 marks (AO2: application)</h5>\n<p><strong>Up to 2 marks per change: 1 for stating what it lets fans do, 1 for explaining the benefit using the scenario. Answers may include:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Large screens</strong> — show action replays during stoppages, so fans in the arena can see a key moment again if they missed it live, keeping them engaged with the match.</li>\n<li><strong>Mobile app</strong> — gives live player statistics during play, so fans can follow extra detail about the game as it happens, rather than relying only on what they can see from their seat.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Accept any other reasonable, applied answer. A description with no benefit, or a benefit not linked to the scenario, earns 1 of the 2 marks for that change.</p>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Discuss how further technology investment at Redcliffe Arena could enhance the experience for spectators both inside and outside the arena.", "marks": 8, "hint": "Choose two or three technologies. For each, explain the benefit for a named group of spectators (inside the venue, or watching elsewhere). Then weigh up the limits. Finish with a judgement.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 8 marks (level-of-response). Read the band you fit, then pick a mark.</h5>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Band 3 (thorough), 6–8:</strong> a balanced, well-applied discussion of several technologies, showing clearly how each enhances the experience for spectators both inside AND outside the arena, weighing the limits (cost, uneven access to the technology, possible distraction from the live action), ending in a justified judgement.</li>\n<li><strong>Band 2 (reasonable), 3–5:</strong> sound understanding applied to more than one technology with some analysis, but the discussion may be one-sided or the judgement unsupported.</li>\n<li><strong>Band 1 (basic), 1–2:</strong> names technologies and/or benefits with little application and no real evaluation; largely a list.</li>\n<li><strong>0 marks:</strong> nothing creditworthy.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Indicative content (indicative, not a checklist — reward valid alternatives)</h5>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Bigger screens:</strong> clearer, more frequent replays for fans inside the arena, helping them follow decisions and enjoy key moments again.</li>\n<li><strong>Live-stats app:</strong> extra detail (e.g. player statistics) for fans both inside and outside the arena, deepening engagement without needing to be at the action itself.</li>\n<li><strong>Extra broadcast cameras:</strong> more camera angles for fans watching on TV or a stream, showing incidents from views a single fixed camera could not.</li>\n<li><strong>Evaluation:</strong> this only helps if fans actually use and can access the technology (not every fan owns a smartphone or wants to look at a screen instead of the game); the investment has a real cost; too many replays or graphics could distract from the live action itself; the benefit may differ for in-arena fans compared with remote fans.</li>\n<li><strong>Judgement:</strong> investment is likely to enhance the experience because it gives both groups of fans clearer information and more to engage with — but only if Redcliffe manages it so the extra technology adds to, rather than distracts from, watching the sport itself.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>"}]}}'::jsonb),
('sport-studies', '5-2-1-positive-effects-of-technology', '5.2.1 Positive Effects of Technology', '{"learn": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "Enhanced performance and a lower risk of injury", "html": "<h4>Enhanced performance</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Technology can give performers and coaches <strong>precise data</strong> that the human eye simply cannot collect — for example, a <strong>GPS vest</strong> worn by a rugby player records exact distance covered, sprint speed and how hard each session was.</li>\n<li>Because training can then target the <em>real</em> weakness shown by the data, rather than a coach''s guess, performance improves faster than it would through trial and error.</li>\n<li>A cyclist using a <strong>power meter</strong> can see the exact wattage they are producing on a climb, so the next session is planned around a genuine number instead of how tired their legs feel.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Lower risk of injury</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Wearable sensors can flag dangerous forces before they cause an injury. A rugby player''s <strong>impact-sensing mouthguard</strong> can record the force of a collision, so medical staff know when to check a player over rather than waiting for a visible symptom.</li>\n<li>Better-designed protective equipment — closer-fitting boots, padded headguards — reduces the chance that a normal knock in a contact sport turns into a serious injury.</li>\n<li>Together, this means technology does not just react to injuries; it helps <strong>prevent</strong> some from happening at all.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "Which of these best explains how a GPS vest could lead to ''enhanced performance''?", "options": ["It gives an exact number for things like distance and speed, so training can target the real weakness it shows", "It automatically and permanently raises the total wages a professional performer is paid by their club every season", "It stops every player at the club from ever picking up an injury again in future", "It plays calming music to the performer throughout a match to help them relax"], "answer": 0, "explain": "A GPS vest measures genuine performance data (distance, speed, effort), letting training target the actual weakness it reveals — not wages, an injury guarantee, or music."}}, {"title": "Quicker recovery from injury and more accurate decisions", "html": "<h4>Quicker recovery from injury</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>When a performer IS injured, technology can speed up a safe return. A <strong>cryotherapy chamber</strong> exposes the body to extreme cold for a short time, which can reduce swelling and pain in the days straight after an injury.</li>\n<li><strong>Compression garments</strong> and underwater treadmills let an injured performer keep some fitness and blood flow moving while the injury itself is still protected.</li>\n<li>Medical staff can also track healing with scans and data instead of guesswork, so a performer returns to full training when the evidence says they are ready — not simply when they say they \"feel fine.\"</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>More accurate decisions</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Ball-tracking and video-review technology gives officials evidence a human eye alone can miss. In tennis, a line-calling system can show whether a ball landed a few millimetres in or out; in football, goal-line technology confirms whether the whole ball crossed the line.</li>\n<li>Because the correct decision is reached more often, the result of the contest is fairer to both sides — settling an argument over a mistaken call that technology could resolve instantly.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "Why can ball-tracking or goal-line technology lead to ''more accurate decisions''?", "options": ["It gives officials clear evidence the naked eye can miss, so the correct decision is reached more often", "It removes the need for a match official to be present at the fixture at all", "It always makes the crowd cheer louder for the home team throughout the fixture", "It guarantees that every single decision from now on will always favour whichever team is currently losing"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Ball-tracking gives evidence the eye can miss, so officials reach the correct decision more often — it does not remove officials, sway crowds, or favour a team."}}, {"title": "Technical analysis — and explaining a positive effect fully", "html": "<h4>Technical analysis</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Technical analysis</strong> means using data or video to study a performer''s technique closely, so a coach can see exactly what to change instead of relying on memory of what happened.</li>\n<li>Filming a swimmer''s stroke, then reviewing it frame by frame, can reveal a small technical flaw — such as an early arm entry — that would be almost impossible to spot live, at full speed, from the poolside.</li>\n<li>Combining video with data such as heart rate or stride length gives an even fuller picture, so feedback to the performer is specific rather than a vague impression.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Explaining a positive effect fully — the exam skill</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A weak answer just names an effect: <em>\"Technology helps with recovery.\"</em> A strong answer names the effect, says HOW the technology produces it, and gives a named sporting example.</li>\n<li>Strong version: <em>\"A cryotherapy chamber can speed up recovery from injury, because the extreme cold reduces swelling in the days straight after the injury happens — for example for an injured rugby player.\"</em></li>\n<li>Keep five positive effects ready to draw on: enhanced performance, lower risk of injury, quicker recovery from injury, more accurate decisions, and technical analysis.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "What makes an exam answer about a positive effect of technology ''full'', rather than basic?", "options": ["Naming the effect, explaining how the technology produces it, and giving a named sporting example", "Simply writing down the name of one piece of sports technology", "Listing as many different pieces of sports technology as you possibly can fit onto the entire page", "Describing your own personal opinion of a professional sports team"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Full marks come from naming the effect, explaining HOW it happens, and applying it to a sporting example — not a bare name, a long list, or an opinion."}}]}, "terms": {"enabled": true, "pairs": [{"term": "Enhanced performance", "definition": "Precise data (e.g. GPS, power meter) lets training target a performer''s real weakness"}, {"term": "Lower risk of injury", "definition": "Sensors and better equipment can flag danger early or reduce harm from a normal knock"}, {"term": "Quicker recovery from injury", "definition": "Treatments like cryotherapy or protected exercise help a performer return to fitness sooner"}, {"term": "More accurate decisions", "definition": "Ball-tracking/video review gives officials evidence the eye alone can miss"}, {"term": "Technical analysis", "definition": "Studying video or data closely (e.g. frame by frame) to see exactly what to change"}, {"term": "Cryotherapy chamber", "definition": "Extreme-cold treatment that can reduce swelling in the days after an injury"}]}, "mcq": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "A cyclist uses a power meter to see the exact wattage they produce on a climb. Which positive effect of technology does this best show?", "options": ["More accurate decisions, because the power meter overturns any decision an official makes in a road race", "Quicker recovery from injury, because the power meter treats sore muscles after every training ride", "Enhanced performance, because training can now target the exact weakness the wattage data reveals", "Technical analysis, because the power meter replaces the need for a coach to ever watch the rider"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Seeing exact wattage lets training target a genuine weakness, which is enhanced performance. A power meter does not overturn decisions, treat muscles, or replace a coach."}, {"question": "A rugby player wears an impact-sensing mouthguard that records the force of collisions. Which positive effect does this best show?", "options": ["Technical analysis, because the mouthguard automatically studies and redesigns the player''s entire long-term training programme", "Lower risk of injury, because the recorded force can prompt a medical check before a visible symptom appears", "More accurate decisions, because the mouthguard decides every refereeing call made during the match", "Enhanced performance, because wearing the mouthguard alone guarantees the player will run faster"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Flagging dangerous force lets staff check a player before symptoms show — that lowers injury risk. It does not redesign training, referee, or guarantee speed."}, {"question": "After surgery, a footballer uses a cryotherapy chamber and an underwater treadmill during rehabilitation. Which positive effect does this best show?", "options": ["Enhanced performance, because the treadmill instantly and permanently makes the footballer much better than before the injury ever happened", "More accurate decisions, because the chamber overturns the referee''s original decision from the match", "Technical analysis, because this equipment films the footballer''s stroke technique frame by frame", "Quicker recovery from injury, because the cold reduces swelling and the treadmill keeps fitness moving safely"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Cold reducing swelling plus safe, protected fitness work is quicker recovery from injury — not instant improvement, a reversed decision, or filmed technique."}, {"question": "A cricket umpire uses ball-tracking technology to check whether a batter would have been out. Which positive effect does this best show?", "options": ["More accurate decisions, because the technology gives evidence of the ball''s path that the eye alone can miss", "Quicker recovery from injury, because the tracking technology instantly and completely heals any injury the batter currently happens to have", "Enhanced performance, because the tracking data alone will make the batter score more runs next innings", "Technical analysis, because the umpire uses the footage to completely redesign the batter''s technique"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Ball-tracking gives evidence the eye can miss, so the correct decision is reached more often — that is more accurate decisions, not healing, scoring, or redesigning technique."}, {"question": "A swimming coach films a swimmer''s stroke and studies it frame by frame after every session. Which positive effect does this best show?", "options": ["More accurate decisions, because the footage can completely change the result of a race that has already finished and been announced", "Lower risk of injury, because filming a swimmer''s stroke prevents every possible muscle strain", "Technical analysis, because the coach can spot a small technical flaw that is hard to see live at full speed", "Enhanced performance, because owning a camera alone raises how fast the swimmer can swim"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Studying video closely to spot a precise flaw is technical analysis — footage does not change a finished result, prevent all strains, or speed a swimmer up by itself."}, {"question": "Which of these describes something that is NOT one of the five positive effects covered on this page?", "options": ["Enhanced performance from a coach using detailed session data", "More accurate decisions made using ball-tracking or video-review technology", "Reduced flow of the game while officials stop to check a replay screen", "Quicker recovery from injury after treatment in a cryotherapy chamber"], "answer": 2, "explain": "A slower, more stop-start game is a downside of technology, not a positive effect — the other three options are all on this page''s list of five positive effects."}]}, "fib": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"text": "Detailed training data can help target a performer''s weakness, which is a form of enhanced [performance]."}, {"text": "Sensors that flag dangerous forces early can help lower the risk of [injury]."}, {"text": "A cryotherapy chamber can reduce swelling, helping a performer make a quicker [recovery] from injury."}, {"text": "Ball-tracking technology gives officials evidence a human eye can miss, leading to more [accurate] decisions."}, {"text": "Studying video or data closely to see exactly what to change is called technical [analysis]."}]}, "tf": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"statement": "Technology can give coaches exact data, such as distance or speed, that the human eye cannot collect alone.", "answer": true, "explain": "That data is exactly what lets training target a performer''s real weakness — the basis of enhanced performance."}, {"statement": "Wearable sensors can only be used to punish a performer after an injury has already happened.", "answer": false, "explain": "Sensors can flag dangerous forces BEFORE an injury, prompting a medical check early — that helps prevent harm, not just react to it."}, {"statement": "A cryotherapy chamber is an example of technology helping a performer recover more quickly from injury.", "answer": true, "explain": "The extreme cold can reduce swelling and pain in the days after an injury, supporting a quicker, safer recovery."}, {"statement": "Ball-tracking and video-review technology can never make an officiating decision more accurate.", "answer": false, "explain": "It gives evidence the human eye can miss, so the correct decision is reached more often — that IS more accurate decisions."}, {"statement": "Technical analysis means using data or video to study technique closely, rather than relying on memory alone.", "answer": true, "explain": "That is the definition — frame-by-frame footage or measurements reveal detail a coach''s memory of the session cannot."}, {"statement": "A strong exam answer about a positive effect only needs to name the effect, with no explanation or example.", "answer": false, "explain": "Naming the effect earns little on its own — full marks need HOW the technology produces it and a named sporting example."}]}, "misc": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"myth": "If I just name a positive effect, like ''enhanced performance'', that is enough for the marks.", "truth": "Naming the effect is usually only the first mark, if that. The examiner wants you to explain HOW the technology produces the effect, ideally with a named sporting example. Basic answer: \"Technology gives enhanced performance.\" Full-marks answer: \"A GPS vest gives a rugby player exact distance and speed data, so training can target their real weakness — enhancing performance.\" The difference is the explanation and the example.", "check": {"question": "An ''Explain'' question asks how technology produces a positive effect. What earns the marks?", "options": ["Naming as many different pieces of sports technology as you can possibly remember", "Naming the effect, then explaining HOW the technology produces it", "Writing the effect''s name in a longer sentence", "Describing your own favourite sports team"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Explain = effect + mechanism (how it happens). Naming technology or lengthening the same sentence without a mechanism does not show the understanding the mark scheme rewards."}}, {"myth": "''Technical analysis'' just means a coach watching the match normally, the same as always.", "truth": "Normal watching, at full speed and from a distance, is exactly what technical analysis improves on. It specifically means using video or data — reviewed frame by frame, or measured precisely — to spot a detail (like an early arm entry) that live watching would miss. If your answer could describe any coach on any touchline, it has not shown technical analysis.", "check": {"question": "What is the key difference between ''technical analysis'' and simply watching a match live?", "options": ["There is no real difference at all between the two things, they are exactly the same idea", "Technical analysis studies video or data closely to spot detail live watching would miss", "Technical analysis means a coach stops watching matches completely", "Technical analysis only ever happens after a performer retires"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Technical analysis uses close, repeatable study (frame by frame, or measured data) to catch detail that live, full-speed watching cannot — that precision is the whole point."}}, {"myth": "''More accurate decisions'' and ''quicker decisions'' mean exactly the same thing.", "truth": "They are different ideas. ''More accurate'' means the correct decision is reached more often, because officials have better evidence. It says nothing about speed — reviewing footage can even take longer than a snap judgement. Don''t swap ''accurate'' for ''quick'' in an answer; they test different understanding.", "check": {"question": "Why is ''more accurate decisions'' a different claim from ''quicker decisions''?", "options": ["Accuracy is about reaching the correct decision, which is separate from how fast it is reached", "A quick decision is always the same thing as a correct decision", "Accurate decisions can only ever be reached completely instantly, and never at all after any kind of review", "There is no meaningful difference between accuracy and speed"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Accuracy is about correctness, not speed — a review can be slower yet still more accurate, so the two ideas must not be confused in an answer."}}]}, "tips": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "Command words for this topic — matching your answer to the tariff", "html": "<p>Positive-effects questions can be short recall or longer applied writing. Match your answer length to the command word:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify / State</strong> — just name the effect. \"Identify one positive effect of technology\" = write its name. 1 mark.</li>\n<li><strong>Describe</strong> — say what the technology does. \"Describe how a cryotherapy chamber helps a performer\" = describe the process.</li>\n<li><strong>Explain</strong> — give the mechanism. Use the word <em>because</em>. \"Explain how video analysis benefits a swimmer\" = the effect PLUS how it happens.</li>\n<li><strong>Discuss / Evaluate</strong> — weigh positives against a limit or a negative, then reach a judgement (usually 6 or 8 marks).</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Read the mark tariff:</strong> [1] wants one point; [4] usually wants two effects applied to a scenario; [6]/[8] level-of-response wants balance and a justified judgement.</p>", "check": {"question": "A question says: ''Explain one positive effect that technology can have on a performer''s recovery. [2]'' What is the safest structure?", "options": ["Name a piece of technology only, with absolutely no further detail given at all", "Name the effect, then explain how the technology produces it", "List every positive effect you can remember", "Describe an unrelated piece of sports equipment"], "answer": 1, "explain": "''Explain'' + [2] rewards a mechanism, not just a name. Listing several effects or describing something unrelated wastes the two marks on offer."}}, {"title": "The golden rule: name the effect, explain how, then give an example", "html": "<p>The single most common way to lose marks here is stopping at the effect''s name. Build every answer as <strong>effect → mechanism → sporting example</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>❌ 0–1 marks:</strong> \"Technology helps with recovery.\"</li>\n<li><strong>✅ full marks:</strong> \"A cryotherapy chamber speeds up recovery from injury, because the extreme cold reduces swelling in the days after the injury happens — for example for an injured rugby player.\"</li>\n</ul>\n<p>In <strong>Section B</strong> the question gives you a scenario (a named club, a named piece of technology). You must then use a detail <em>from that scenario</em>, not a generic example.</p>", "check": {"question": "In a Section B scenario about a named club buying named technology, your explanation should be built around...", "options": ["any sport that you personally happen to enjoy watching in your own free time", "the specific technology and scenario you are given", "a famous athlete unrelated to the scenario", "your own school''s PE lessons only"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Section B is applied — the marks are for using the scenario''s own technology and detail. A generic example that ignores the scenario is capped."}}, {"title": "Where this topic appears + sentence starters", "html": "<p><strong>Where it shows up:</strong> positive effects appear as quick recall in <strong>Section A</strong> (identify/explain), as applied points in <strong>Section B</strong> scenarios about a club or performer using new technology, and they feed <strong>Section C</strong> 8-mark Discuss/Evaluate answers weighing technology''s positives against its costs or limits.</p>\n<p><strong>Three punchy tips:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Keep all five effects ready: enhanced performance, lower risk of injury, quicker recovery, more accurate decisions, technical analysis.</li>\n<li>For every effect, memorise one worked mechanism (like the cryotherapy example) so you always have a full sentence ready.</li>\n<li>In a longer answer, don''t just list effects — pick two or three and develop each one properly.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Sentence starters for a longer answer:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\"One positive effect here is… because…\"</li>\n<li>\"This benefits the performer by… which shows…\"</li>\n<li>\"However, this benefit depends on… so overall…\"</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "Why is it better to develop two or three positive effects properly than to list five?", "options": ["Listing five effects by name is always worth far more marks than developing just two of them", "A developed explanation with a mechanism earns more than a bare list of names", "The exam only ever allows one effect to be mentioned", "Developing an effect means giving your personal opinion instead"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Marks come from mechanism and application, not from how many names appear — two well-developed effects out-score five bare names."}}]}, "exam": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "Identify <strong>two</strong> positive effects that technology can have on sports performers.", "marks": 2, "hint": "Just name two — pick from the five on this page: enhanced performance, lower risk of injury, quicker recovery from injury, more accurate decisions, technical analysis.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 2 marks (AO1)</h5>\n<p><strong>1 mark for each correct positive effect named, to a maximum of two. Accept any two different effects from:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Enhanced performance</li>\n<li>Lower risk of injury</li>\n<li>Quicker recovery from injury</li>\n<li>More accurate decisions</li>\n<li>Technical analysis</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Do not credit the same effect written twice.</p>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Which of these is an example of technology producing a positive effect through ''more accurate decisions''?", "marks": 1, "hint": "Think about which option gives officials evidence the eye alone can miss.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — Ball-tracking technology confirming exactly where a tennis ball landed.</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>This gives an official evidence the eye alone can miss, so the correct decision is reached more often.</li>\n<li>The other options show enhanced performance, quicker recovery, and technical analysis instead.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Explain how Thornfield RFC''s investment in GPS vests and a cryotherapy chamber could produce <strong>two</strong> positive effects for its players.", "marks": 4, "hint": "Take each piece of technology in turn. Name the positive effect it produces, then explain how, using details from the scenario.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 4 marks (AO2: application)</h5>\n<p><strong>Up to 2 marks per piece of technology: 1 for identifying a relevant positive effect, 1 for explaining it using the scenario. Answers may include:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>GPS vests</strong> — enhanced performance: the vests record exact distance and effort for every Thornfield player, so training can target each player''s real weakness rather than a guess.</li>\n<li><strong>Cryotherapy chamber</strong> — quicker recovery from injury: the extreme cold reduces swelling in the days after an injury, helping an injured Thornfield player return to training sooner.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Accept any other reasonable, applied answer. An effect with no mechanism, or a mechanism not linked to the scenario, earns 1 of the 2 marks for that item.</p>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Discuss the extent to which investing in technology would produce positive effects for Portway Swimming Academy''s swimmers.", "marks": 8, "hint": "Pick two or three positive effects and apply each to Portway''s plan. Then weigh it up — what limits how much the investment would really help? Finish with a judgement.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 8 marks (level-of-response). Read the band you fit, then pick a mark.</h5>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Band 3 (thorough), 6–8:</strong> a balanced, well-applied discussion of several positive effects for Portway, showing clearly how the technology would benefit swimmers AND weighing the limits (cost, staff skill, whether the data is actually used well), ending in a justified judgement.</li>\n<li><strong>Band 2 (reasonable), 3–5:</strong> sound understanding applied to more than one effect with some analysis, but the discussion may be one-sided or the judgement unsupported.</li>\n<li><strong>Band 1 (basic), 1–2:</strong> names effects and/or technology with little application and no real evaluation; largely a list.</li>\n<li><strong>0 marks:</strong> nothing creditworthy.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Indicative content (indicative, not a checklist — reward valid alternatives)</h5>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Wearable trackers:</strong> give exact effort and speed data for each swimmer, so training can target a genuine weakness — enhanced performance.</li>\n<li><strong>Video-analysis suite:</strong> lets a coach study a swimmer''s stroke frame by frame, spotting a small technical flaw live watching would miss — technical analysis.</li>\n<li><strong>Touch-pad timing technology:</strong> gives a far more accurate result in a close finish than a human eye could judge alone — more accurate decisions.</li>\n<li><strong>Evaluation:</strong> the benefit only appears if coaching staff have the time and skill to act on the data, not just collect it; the equipment is expensive for an academy that currently spends little on technology; a smaller or poorer academy might not be able to match this investment at all.</li>\n<li><strong>Judgement:</strong> investing in technology is likely to help Portway''s swimmers improve, because it targets real weaknesses and details that watching alone would miss — but the benefit depends on the academy affording it and using the data well, not on owning the equipment alone.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>"}]}}'::jsonb),
('sport-studies', '5-2-2-negative-effects-of-technology', '5.2.2 Negative Effects of Technology', '{"learn": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "Unequal access and rising cost", "html": "<h4>Not every team can afford the same kit</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>New technology is usually <strong>expensive</strong> when it first appears — cameras, sensors, materials and the software behind them all cost money to develop and buy.</li>\n<li>That cost creates <strong>unequal access</strong>: a wealthy club or a wealthy nation can buy the newest equipment, while a poorer club or nation cannot. The richer side then gains an <strong>advantage</strong> that has nothing to do with the players'' actual ability.</li>\n<li>Example: a well-funded cycling team can afford aerodynamic skinsuits and custom-built bike frames that a smaller national team simply cannot buy, so the smaller team competes at a disadvantage before the race even starts.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Cost keeps climbing</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>As technology advances, each new version tends to cost <strong>more</strong>, not less — governing bodies, clubs and venues have to keep spending to stay up to date.</li>\n<li>That spending has to come from somewhere: often ticket prices, membership fees or grassroots budgets, which can mean less money reaching participation at the bottom of the sport.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "Why can new sports technology create unequal access between teams or nations?", "options": ["Because all governing bodies are legally required to share every new invention with every other nation immediately", "Because it is usually expensive, so only wealthier teams or nations can afford to buy and benefit from it", "Because officials will not allow poorer teams to use any technology at all under any circumstances", "Because technology never actually improves a team''s performance in any measurable way"], "answer": 1, "explain": "New technology tends to be costly, so wealthier teams and nations can buy an advantage that poorer ones cannot afford — that is the unequal-access problem."}}, {"title": "Availability and affordability problems", "html": "<h4>Two related but different problems</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Affordability</strong> is about price — a club, school or individual simply cannot pay for the technology.</li>\n<li><strong>Availability</strong> is about supply — even a club that could pay might not be able to get hold of the technology at all, because it is rare, still being trialled, or only used at the very top level of the sport.</li>\n<li>Example: goal-line technology is standard in a top professional football league, but a grassroots Sunday league pitch is unlikely to ever have it — the cost of installing and running the cameras and sensors makes it completely unavailable at that level.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Why this matters for participation and fairness</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>If only elite performers ever experience a piece of technology (say, an altitude training chamber or a biomechanics lab), then talented performers without access to it can be left behind, even if they train just as hard.</li>\n<li>This links back to unequal access: cost and availability together mean that technology can widen the gap between the best-funded performers and everyone else, rather than making competition fairer.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "A grassroots pitch cannot get goal-line technology installed at any price because hardly any suppliers offer it at that level. This is mainly a problem of...", "options": ["officiating bias shown specifically and deliberately against smaller, lower-funded grassroots teams", "availability, since the technology is not accessible at that level regardless of budget", "the rules of the sport banning grassroots technology outright", "player fitness rather than technology at all"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Availability is about the technology simply not being obtainable at that level, which is different from affordability (being too expensive but technically obtainable)."}}, {"title": "Slowing the game down and over-relying on the decision", "html": "<h4>Reduced flow of the game</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Officiating technology (such as a video review) usually means the game must <strong>stop</strong> while the check happens. That stoppage breaks up the natural rhythm, or <strong>flow</strong>, of the contest.</li>\n<li>Example: a rugby referee sending a decision \"upstairs\" to the Television Match Official can pause play for over a minute, cooling down the crowd''s atmosphere and interrupting the momentum of the team that was attacking.</li>\n<li>The more often technology is used to check decisions, the more often the game is interrupted — so a technology that improves accuracy can still be criticised for making the contest less enjoyable to play and to watch.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Over-influenced officials</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A separate problem: officials can become <strong>over-reliant</strong> on technology, treating what the screen or sensor shows as automatically correct, even when the technology does not capture the full picture or the correct interpretation of the rule.</li>\n<li>Example: a football assistant referee might wait for a marginal offside decision to be confirmed by the technology instead of trusting their own read of the passage of play, even in situations the technology was never designed to judge precisely.</li>\n<li>The exam skill: don''t just say \"technology causes problems\" — <strong>name the specific negative</strong> (unequal access, cost, availability, reduced flow, over-reliance) and back it with a sport-specific example.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "Which of these best describes ''reduced flow of the game'' as a negative effect of technology?", "options": ["Officiating technology can cause stoppages that interrupt the natural rhythm of play", "Technology always makes every single match finish far more quickly than it ever did before it existed", "Players become less fit because technology does the exercise for them", "Spectators are no longer allowed to watch matches that use technology"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Checks and reviews take time, and that stoppage interrupts the momentum and rhythm of the contest — that is what ''reduced flow'' means."}}]}, "terms": {"enabled": true, "pairs": [{"term": "Unequal access", "definition": "Wealthier teams/nations can afford technology poorer ones cannot, gaining an advantage"}, {"term": "Increased cost", "definition": "Newer sports technology tends to be expensive, and cost often keeps rising"}, {"term": "Affordability", "definition": "A price problem — a club or performer cannot pay for the technology"}, {"term": "Availability", "definition": "A supply problem — the technology cannot be obtained at that level at all"}, {"term": "Reduced flow of the game", "definition": "Officiating stoppages for reviews interrupt the rhythm of play"}, {"term": "Over-influenced officials", "definition": "Officials treat technology''s output as automatically correct beyond its real limits"}]}, "mcq": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "Why might a wealthy national team gain an advantage purely from technology?", "options": ["Because expensive new equipment is often only affordable to well-funded teams or nations", "Because officials are told to favour whichever team owns the most technology", "Because technology automatically disqualifies any team that cannot afford it", "Because poorer nations are officially banned by every governing body''s written rules from using such equipment"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Cost is the barrier — a wealthy team can buy an edge that a poorer one simply cannot afford, which is the unequal-access problem, not a rule or an official''s bias."}, {"question": "A small athletics club cannot get access to a biomechanics lab because almost no supplier offers one outside elite programmes. This is best described as a problem of...", "options": ["motivation, since the athletes involved are simply not trying hard enough to go and find one anywhere nearby", "availability, because the technology is not obtainable at that level regardless of funding", "rule-breaking, because using such labs is against the sport''s official rules", "officiating, because referees control who is allowed to use training technology"], "answer": 1, "explain": "When a technology simply is not offered or accessible at a level, that is an availability problem, separate from cost (affordability) or rules."}, {"question": "Which of these is a genuine downside of officials using video review technology?", "options": ["It can slow the game down and reduce its natural flow while the check takes place", "It makes every single decision instantly and with absolutely no delay whatsoever", "It removes the need for any officials to be present at a fixture ever again", "It guarantees every decision will always be perfectly correct with no possible dispute"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Reviews take time, and that pause interrupts the rhythm of the contest — the other options overstate what the technology actually delivers."}, {"question": "What does it mean if an official becomes ''over-influenced'' by technology?", "options": ["They ignore the technology completely and always trust their own on-field judgement over it instead", "They treat the technology''s output as automatically correct, even outside its real limits", "They ask a second official to make every single decision instead of using any technology", "They stop the fixture permanently until new equipment can be purchased and installed"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Over-reliance means trusting the technology as final even in situations where it may not give the best interpretation of the rules."}, {"question": "As sports technology advances, what typically happens to its cost over time?", "options": ["It falls so quickly and so reliably that every grassroots club can easily afford it within just a year", "It usually stays high or keeps rising, since newer versions cost more to develop", "It becomes completely free once a governing body approves it for use", "It has no relationship at all with how advanced or recent the technology is"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Advancing technology tends to keep costs high or rising, which is part of why affordability remains a recurring problem for smaller clubs."}, {"question": "A rugby TMO review pauses play for over a minute during an attacking passage of play. This mainly illustrates...", "options": ["greatly improved availability of officiating technology reaching every single grassroots level fixture", "reduced flow of the game caused by an officiating stoppage", "unequal access between two professional teams", "the complete removal of the on-field referee''s authority"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The stoppage interrupts the momentum of play, which is exactly what ''reduced flow of the game'' describes."}]}, "fib": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"text": "Expensive new technology can create [unequal] access, since only wealthier teams or nations can afford it."}, {"text": "The [cost] of new sports technology tends to keep rising as it advances."}, {"text": "A club that cannot pay for technology has an [affordability] problem."}, {"text": "A club that cannot obtain a technology at all, whatever its budget, faces an [availability] problem."}, {"text": "Video review stoppages can reduce the [flow] of the game by interrupting its rhythm."}]}, "tf": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"statement": "New sports technology is usually expensive, which can create unequal access between wealthier and poorer teams.", "answer": true, "explain": "Cost is the main driver of unequal access — richer teams and nations can buy an advantage that poorer ones cannot afford."}, {"statement": "Availability and affordability mean exactly the same thing.", "answer": false, "explain": "Affordability is about price; availability is about whether the technology can be obtained at all, even with money to spend."}, {"statement": "As sports technology advances, its cost usually falls, making it cheaper for everyone straight away.", "answer": false, "explain": "Newer technology tends to stay expensive or get more costly, not cheaper, which keeps affordability a live problem."}, {"statement": "Officiating technology can reduce the flow of a game because checking a decision often causes a stoppage.", "answer": true, "explain": "Reviews take time, and that pause interrupts the natural rhythm and momentum of play."}, {"statement": "An official who is ''over-influenced'' by technology always ignores what the technology shows.", "answer": false, "explain": "Over-influenced means the opposite — trusting the technology''s output as automatically correct, even beyond its real limits."}, {"statement": "Technology can sometimes give the best-funded performers an advantage that has nothing to do with their actual ability.", "answer": true, "explain": "That is the unequal-access problem — the advantage comes from money, not from greater skill or effort."}]}, "misc": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"myth": "Technology in sport only ever has positive effects — more accuracy, better performance, nothing to worry about.", "truth": "The specification specifically tests the NEGATIVES too. Unequal access, rising cost, availability/affordability problems, reduced flow of the game, and officials becoming over-influenced by technology are all genuine downsides, even where the technology also helps. A balanced exam answer weighs both sides.", "check": {"question": "Which of these is a genuine negative effect the specification expects you to know?", "options": ["Technology always makes officiating completely free of charge for every club", "Unequal access can give wealthier teams or nations an advantage", "Technology has literally no effect on the game whatsoever", "Every spectator always prefers a game with zero technology involved"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Unequal access is one of the named negatives — cost creates an advantage that has nothing to do with ability."}}, {"myth": "Affordability and availability are just two words for the same problem.", "truth": "They are related but different. Affordability is about PRICE — a club cannot pay for it. Availability is about SUPPLY — even with money, the technology might not be offered at that level at all. A grassroots pitch may not get goal-line technology at any price, which is an availability problem, not just a cost one.", "check": {"question": "A club has the budget to buy a technology, but no supplier will sell it at that level. This is mainly a problem of...", "options": ["affordability", "availability", "officiating bias", "player motivation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Having the money but no way to obtain the technology is an availability problem, distinct from affordability."}}, {"myth": "A video review stopping play is only ever a good thing, because it makes the decision more accurate.", "truth": "Accuracy and flow are a genuine trade-off. A review can improve the accuracy of a decision while still damaging the flow of the game, because play has to stop while it happens. Good exam answers can hold both ideas at once, rather than treating the stoppage as automatically worth it.", "check": {"question": "Why can a review that improves accuracy still be criticised?", "options": ["Because it can reduce the flow of the game by causing a stoppage", "Because accurate decisions are against the official rules of every sport", "Because reviews are always slower than officials without any technology at all", "Because spectators are not allowed to watch a review taking place"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The trade-off is flow versus accuracy — a stoppage to check a decision interrupts the rhythm of play even if it gets the call right."}}]}, "tips": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "Command words and mark tariffs for this topic", "html": "<p>Negative-effects questions scale with the command word and the marks available:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>State / Identify [1]</strong> — name one negative, nothing more. \"State one negative effect of using technology in sport\" = a single named point.</li>\n<li><strong>Explain [2–4]</strong> — name the negative, then give the reason or the sport-specific example that shows you understand it. Two linked points, or one point developed with an example, usually matches a [2] tariff.</li>\n<li><strong>Discuss / Evaluate [8]</strong> — cover more than one negative, apply them to the scenario, and weigh them against a positive before reaching a judgement. A list of negatives with no weighing rarely leaves Band 1.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Read the tariff before you write</strong> — a [2] question does not need five points, and an [8] question needs far more than a list.</p>", "check": {"question": "A question asks ''State one negative effect of technology in sport [1]''. What is the safest answer?", "options": ["A single named negative effect", "A full paragraph covering every negative you know", "Two negatives explained in detail", "A description of a positive effect instead"], "answer": 0, "explain": "''State'' + [1] wants one named point — writing more wastes time without earning extra marks."}}, {"title": "Always attach a named-sport example", "html": "<p>A negative named on its own is thin. Build every point as <strong>negative → named sport → what actually happens</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>❌ weak:</strong> \"Technology costs a lot of money.\"</li>\n<li><strong>✅ strong:</strong> \"In cycling, aerodynamic equipment is expensive, so a well-funded team can afford gains a smaller national team cannot, giving them an advantage unrelated to ability.\"</li>\n</ul>\n<p>In <strong>Section B</strong>, take the example from the scenario you are given rather than a general one you already knew.</p>", "check": {"question": "Why does naming a specific sport strengthen an answer about a negative effect of technology?", "options": ["It shows how the negative actually plays out in a real situation", "It is required purely to fill up space on the page", "It completely replaces the need to ever name the negative effect at all anywhere in the answer", "It is only needed in Section C and never elsewhere"], "answer": 0, "explain": "A concrete sporting example demonstrates real understanding of how the negative effect operates, not just that it exists."}}, {"title": "Building a balanced Discuss/Evaluate answer", "html": "<p>An 8-mark Discuss question usually wants you to weigh negatives against at least one positive, then reach a supported judgement.</p>\n<p><strong>Three sentence starters to build the structure:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\"One negative effect is… which affects [named sport] because…\"</li>\n<li>\"However, technology also… which is a genuine benefit because…\"</li>\n<li>\"Overall, the negatives outweigh/are outweighed by the positives because…\"</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Never stop at a list — the top band needs the weighing and the final judgement, not just more points.</p>", "check": {"question": "What usually separates a top-band Discuss answer from a middle-band one on this topic?", "options": ["Writing about a much longer list of negatives with no weighing", "Weighing negatives against positives and reaching a justified judgement", "Only ever mentioning negative effects and ignoring positives completely", "Repeating the same point using slightly different wording each time"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Top-band answers weigh both sides and land on a justified judgement — a longer list alone does not move up a band."}}]}, "exam": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "State <strong>two</strong> negative effects of using technology in sport.", "marks": 2, "hint": "Pick two different negatives — for example unequal access, increased cost, availability/affordability, reduced flow of the game, or officials being over-influenced.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 2 marks (AO1)</h5>\n<p><strong>1 mark for each different correct negative effect named, to a maximum of two. Accept any two from:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Unequal access to technology between teams/nations</li>\n<li>Increased cost of new technology</li>\n<li>Problems of availability</li>\n<li>Problems of affordability</li>\n<li>Reduced flow of the game caused by officiating stoppages</li>\n<li>Officials being over-influenced by technology</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Do not credit the same negative written twice, or a positive effect.</p>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Which of these best describes a negative effect of officiating technology on the flow of a game?", "marks": 1, "hint": "Think about what happens to play while a review is being checked.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — It can cause stoppages that interrupt the rhythm and momentum of play.</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Checking a decision takes time, and that pause is the \"reduced flow\" problem.</li>\n<li>The other options overstate or misdescribe what officiating technology actually does.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Explain <strong>two</strong> negative effects of technology shown by this scenario.", "marks": 4, "hint": "Look for two different negatives in the scenario — the price difference between the clubs, and the fact Ferrow Town cannot find the equipment anywhere at all.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 4 marks (AO2: application)</h5>\n<p><strong>Up to 2 marks per negative effect: 1 for naming it, 1 for a reason/detail linked to the scenario. Accept:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Unequal access / increased cost</strong> — the wealthier neighbouring club can afford the several-thousand-pound spikes, giving its sprinters a technique-feedback advantage that Ferrow Town''s sprinters do not get, unrelated to their ability.</li>\n<li><strong>Availability</strong> — Ferrow Town cannot find even a cheaper or second-hand version anywhere, showing the technology is not just expensive but hard to obtain at their level at all.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Accept any other reasonable, applied answer using scenario detail. A named effect with no scenario link earns 1 of the 2 marks for that point.</p>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Discuss the negative effects of technology on sport, using examples to support your answer.", "marks": 8, "hint": "Cover more than one negative (cost/unequal access, availability, reduced flow, over-influenced officials). Briefly weigh these against a positive, then give a justified judgement.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 8 marks (level-of-response). Read the band you fit, then pick a mark.</h5>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Band 3 (thorough), 6–8:</strong> a balanced discussion of several negative effects with named-sport examples, weighed against at least one genuine positive, ending in a justified judgement.</li>\n<li><strong>Band 2 (reasonable), 3–5:</strong> sound coverage of more than one negative effect with some examples, but limited weighing or an unsupported judgement.</li>\n<li><strong>Band 1 (basic), 1–2:</strong> names one or more negatives with little explanation or example, largely a list, no real evaluation.</li>\n<li><strong>0 marks:</strong> nothing creditworthy.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Indicative content (indicative, not a checklist — reward valid alternatives)</h5>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Unequal access / increased cost:</strong> wealthier clubs or nations can buy an advantage (e.g. sensor spikes, aerodynamic kit) that smaller clubs like Ferrow Town cannot afford.</li>\n<li><strong>Availability:</strong> some technology simply is not offered at grassroots level, regardless of budget (e.g. a small club unable to find equipment at any price).</li>\n<li><strong>Reduced flow of the game:</strong> officiating checks (e.g. a review at a major meeting) pause competition and disrupt momentum.</li>\n<li><strong>Over-influenced officials:</strong> officials may treat a marginal reading as automatically correct even where the technology was not designed to judge it precisely.</li>\n<li><strong>Balance:</strong> technology can also improve accuracy, safety or performance, so the negatives are a trade-off rather than a reason to reject technology outright.</li>\n<li><strong>Judgement:</strong> the negatives are real and hit smaller clubs hardest, but they are a cost of an overall improvement in accuracy and safety — the fairest conclusion is that access needs addressing (e.g. shared/subsidised equipment) rather than technology being avoided altogether.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>"}]}}'::jsonb),
('sport-studies', '5-2-3-technology-and-the-spectator-experience', '5.2.3 Technology and the Spectator Experience', '{"learn": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "Technology and the crowd inside the stadium — the positives", "html": "<h4>Understanding decisions, not just guessing</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Many sports now show a <strong>technology-based decision</strong> on the stadium''s big screen — for example a video review of a contested goal, or a graphic showing whether a shot landed in or out.</li>\n<li>Seeing the same replay the officials used helps spectators <strong>follow the action and understand why a decision was given</strong>, instead of hearing an announcement with no evidence behind it.</li>\n<li>This makes big decisions feel more open and fair, because the whole crowd can judge the evidence for itself rather than simply trusting an official''s word.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Big screens do more than show replays</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Big screens can also show <strong>scores and stats from other fixtures</strong>, close-up replays of skilful moments, and information that keeps spectators engaged even during a stoppage in play.</li>\n<li><strong>Named example:</strong> at a football match, a big screen showing the video-review footage of a disputed goal-line incident lets the crowd see the same picture the video official is using, rather than waiting for an announcement alone.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "What does a stadium big screen replay mainly give spectators?", "options": ["A guarantee that the crowd''s preferred team will always benefit from the final decision", "The power to personally replace an official who has made an unpopular decision", "The same evidence the officials used, helping them understand why a decision was given", "A permanent recording that spectators are allowed to keep and take home after the match"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The value of a replay is that it shows fans the evidence behind a decision, building understanding — not favouring a team, replacing officials, or acting as a keepsake."}}, {"title": "Technology and the audience watching from home — the positives", "html": "<h4>A deeper picture than a stadium seat can give</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Broadcasters can add <strong>graphics and statistics</strong> to the picture — for example a graphic showing possession, distance covered, or exactly where a ball crossed a line — detail a spectator in a stadium seat cannot see.</li>\n<li>Multiple camera angles and slow-motion replays let a home viewer study a controversial moment from angles the on-field official never had, adding to their understanding and enjoyment of the contest.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Named example</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Ball-tracking technology</strong>, used in sports such as cricket and tennis broadcasts, turns a fast, hard-to-see moment into a clear graphic, so a home viewer can follow a decision as confidently as an expert watching live.</li>\n<li>Overall, this extra layer of detail is one reason many fans say watching from home has become a genuinely richer experience than it used to be.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "Which of these best explains why home viewing has been enhanced by technology?", "options": ["Home viewers now receive a private vote on every contested decision during the game", "Broadcast graphics, statistics and extra camera angles add detail a stadium seat cannot give", "Every home broadcast is now required by law to remove all forms of camera replay", "Home viewers can only ever watch short highlights and are never shown the match as it happens live"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Extra graphics, stats and camera angles are the genuine reason home viewing has improved — there is no viewer vote, no ban on replays, and live coverage still happens."}}, {"title": "The negatives — and judging whether technology is \"suitable\"", "html": "<h4>Waiting breaks the atmosphere</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A video review can take a minute or more, and that wait can <strong>break the atmosphere and tension</strong> in the stadium — the crowd''s noise dies down and the pace of the contest is interrupted.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Screens can distract from the live action</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Spectators (and sometimes commentators) can end up staring at a screen replay of the last incident and <strong>miss the next passage of play</strong> happening live in front of them — an over-reliance on screens.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Cost</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Cameras, review systems and big screens are expensive to install and run. That cost can be passed on through <strong>higher ticket prices or paid subscription tiers</strong>, which can price some spectators out altogether.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Feeling less \"human\"</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Some fans feel a contest loses some of its human character when every close moment is paused for a technological check, rather than trusting an official''s instant judgement.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Suitability — the evaluation skill</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Not every sport, venue or decision needs the same level of technology. The real question is whether a review is <strong>important enough to justify its cost and delay</strong> — a major final may justify it more than a small local fixture.</li>\n<li><strong>Named example:</strong> a small, non-televised local match is unlikely to have (or need) the same big-screen review system as a major televised final, because the cost would not be justified by the benefit.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "Judging the \"suitability\" of technology for the spectator experience mainly means...?", "options": ["Assuming every single venue must install the most expensive technology that is currently available", "Ignoring how much a review costs, since only the delay it causes really matters", "Deciding that no sport should ever use any form of review technology at all", "Weighing whether the benefit of using it is worth its cost and delay for that event"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Suitability is about weighing benefit against cost and delay for that particular event — not assuming maximum technology everywhere, ignoring cost, or banning it outright."}}]}, "terms": {"enabled": true, "pairs": [{"term": "Big screen replay", "definition": "Stadium footage of a decision that lets fans see the evidence and understand the call"}, {"term": "Broadcast graphics", "definition": "On-screen statistics and info added for home viewers, deepening their understanding"}, {"term": "Ball-tracking technology", "definition": "Turns a fast or hard-to-see moment into a clear graphic for viewers"}, {"term": "Atmosphere", "definition": "The crowd''s noise, tension and excitement — often interrupted by a long delay"}, {"term": "Over-reliance on screens", "definition": "Watching a replay so closely that you miss the next live action in front of you"}, {"term": "Suitability of technology", "definition": "Whether a review is worth its cost and delay for that sport, venue or decision"}]}, "mcq": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "What is the main benefit of a big screen replay for spectators inside a stadium?", "options": ["It lets fans see the same replay evidence as the match officials, which builds trust in the decision", "It gives the crowd a formal vote that can overturn any refereeing decision it strongly dislikes, no matter what", "It ends the referee''s involvement in the game completely from that moment onwards", "It exists only to fill the silence while the refreshment stalls remain open for business"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Seeing the same evidence as the officials helps fans understand a decision and builds trust. It does not give the crowd a vote, remove the referee, or exist only to sell refreshments."}, {"question": "Why can watching a match at home now be a richer experience than in the past?", "options": ["Broadcast graphics and statistics on screen help viewers understand the contest in far more depth", "Home viewers are given a private link that lets them personally overrule any decision that is given", "Every match can now legally only be watched on a television screen and nowhere else at all", "Extra camera angles are shown, but broadcasters are never permitted to include any replay"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Extra statistics and graphics genuinely add understanding for a home audience. Viewers cannot overrule decisions, matches are not television-only, and replays are a normal part of modern broadcasts."}, {"question": "What is a genuine negative effect of a long wait for a technology-based decision?", "options": ["It can break the atmosphere and tension that the crowd had built up before the review", "It always guarantees that the original, on-field decision will be proven completely correct", "It permanently removes the need for any official to be present at future matches", "It stops every single spectator from being able to follow the rest of that match"], "answer": 0, "explain": "A long delay genuinely interrupts a stadium''s pace and quietens the crowd. It does not guarantee the original decision was right, remove officials, or stop fans following the rest of the game."}, {"question": "How can over-reliance on big screens reduce a spectator''s experience?", "options": ["Spectators can end up watching the replay so closely that they miss the next live action", "Spectators are legally required to look only at the pitch and never at any screen", "Screens automatically make every single crowd completely silent for the rest of the match", "Screens remove all further need for spectators to buy a ticket in future"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Staring at a replay can mean missing what happens live next, which is the real downside. There is no legal rule about where fans look, and screens do not silence crowds or remove the need for tickets."}, {"question": "How can the cost of spectator technology affect fans?", "options": ["It can be passed on through higher ticket prices or a paid subscription for extra footage", "It always reduces every single ticket price at every stadium that installs brand new technology", "It has no effect at all on prices because governing bodies fully cover every cost", "It only affects players'' wages and never touches anything that a spectator pays"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Clubs and broadcasters often recover the cost of technology through fans'' ticket or subscription prices. It does not reduce prices, get fully covered elsewhere, or avoid spectators altogether."}, {"question": "What does it mean to judge the ''suitability'' of technology for a fixture?", "options": ["Weighing whether the benefit of a review is worth its cost and delay for that particular event", "Assuming every single fixture, however small in size, needs the exact same amount of review technology", "Deciding that only the most expensive technology available can ever be worth using", "Ignoring cost completely, since delay is the only thing that ever matters to a crowd"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Suitability means balancing the benefit of getting a decision right against the cost and delay involved for that event. It is not about using maximum technology everywhere, or ignoring cost."}]}, "fib": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"text": "Big screens let fans see the same [evidence] the officials used to reach a decision."}, {"text": "Broadcast graphics and [statistics] help home viewers understand the contest in more depth."}, {"text": "A long wait for a video review can break the [atmosphere] inside the stadium."}, {"text": "Installing and running review technology is expensive, which can raise ticket or subscription [prices]."}, {"text": "Judging whether a review is worth its cost and delay for a fixture is about the [suitability] of the technology."}]}, "tf": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"statement": "Big screen replays can help spectators understand why a decision was given.", "answer": true, "explain": "Seeing the same evidence as the officials is exactly why replays help spectators follow and understand the game."}, {"statement": "Watching a match at home has become richer partly because of on-screen statistics and graphics.", "answer": true, "explain": "Broadcast graphics and stats add detail a stadium seat cannot give, which is a genuine positive effect for home viewers."}, {"statement": "A long wait for a technology-based decision has no effect on a stadium''s atmosphere.", "answer": false, "explain": "A long review genuinely breaks the crowd''s atmosphere and interrupts the pace of the contest — it is a real negative effect."}, {"statement": "The cost of installing review technology can never affect ticket or subscription prices.", "answer": false, "explain": "Clubs and broadcasters often pass the cost of technology on through higher ticket prices or paid subscriptions."}, {"statement": "Every sport and venue needs exactly the same amount of review technology, regardless of cost.", "answer": false, "explain": "Suitability means weighing the benefit against the cost and delay for that event — a small fixture may not need what a major final does."}, {"statement": "Some fans feel a contest can feel less \"human\" when every close moment is checked by technology.", "answer": true, "explain": "This is a genuine criticism — some spectators feel the game loses spontaneity when officials'' instant judgement is replaced by a pause for review."}]}, "misc": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"myth": "For a longer question on this topic, naming one positive effect of technology is enough to answer it well.", "truth": "Naming one effect only ever earns a fraction of the marks. Section B and C questions expect BOTH a positive and a negative effect, applied to the scenario, and Section C additionally wants a final judgement about which matters more. A single named effect caps the answer in the lowest band.", "check": {"question": "For a Section C ''Discuss'' question on this topic, naming one positive effect alone will...?", "options": ["Always earn full marks, because one clearly named effect is all that is ever required", "Cap the answer in the lowest band, since both sides and a judgement are expected", "Automatically move the answer into the top band without needing anything else", "Disqualify the whole answer completely, scoring zero marks under any circumstances"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Discuss/Evaluate questions need both sides plus a judgement; one named effect on its own caps the answer in the basic band, though it is not disqualified outright."}}, {"myth": "A long video review doesn''t really matter to the crowd because it only takes a minute or so.", "truth": "Even a short delay is credited as a genuine negative effect, because it interrupts the atmosphere and pace the crowd had built up. Mark schemes reward students who explain WHY the wait matters (broken tension, quietened crowd), not just that a wait happened.", "check": {"question": "Why does a mark scheme credit ''a long wait for a decision'' as a genuine negative effect?", "options": ["Because waiting always causes every single official''s original decision to be reversed", "Because a wait of any length is against the official rules of every sport", "Because even a short delay can break the crowd''s atmosphere and interrupt the pace", "Because waiting removes any further need for spectators to hold a valid ticket"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The genuine negative is the interruption to atmosphere and pace, however brief the wait feels — it is not about rule-breaking, guaranteed reversals, or tickets."}}, {"myth": "Every stadium and every sport should use as much review technology as possible, since more technology is always better.", "truth": "The exam rewards the opposite idea: suitability. A review is only worth having if its benefit (accuracy, fan understanding) justifies its cost and the delay it causes for that particular fixture. A small local match may not need — or be able to afford — the same technology as a major televised final.", "check": {"question": "Why is ''more technology is always better'' a misconception on this topic?", "options": ["Because suitability means weighing a review''s benefit against its real cost and delay", "Because technology has never once been shown to help any spectator understand a decision", "Because every governing body has permanently banned technology from all major events", "Because spectators are legally forbidden from watching any form of screen replay"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The correct idea is suitability — balancing benefit against cost and delay — not that technology never helps, is banned, or that replays are forbidden."}}]}, "tips": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "Command words for this topic — what each one wants", "html": "<p>Questions on the spectator experience are usually applied or evaluative. Match your answer to the command word:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify / State</strong> — just name an effect. \"Identify one positive effect of technology on spectators [1]\" = one clear effect, nothing more.</li>\n<li><strong>Explain</strong> — give a reason. \"Explain how technology could reduce a spectator''s experience\" = an effect <em>plus</em> why it reduces the experience.</li>\n<li><strong>Discuss / Evaluate</strong> — weigh BOTH sides (positive and negative) and reach a judgement about which matters more, using the scenario.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Read the mark tariff:</strong> [1]–[2] wants brief points; higher-mark Section B questions want points applied to the scenario; the 8-mark Section C question always wants both sides plus a judgement.</p>", "check": {"question": "A question says: ''Discuss whether technology has improved the spectator experience [8]''. What earns the top band?", "options": ["Naming a single positive effect and stopping the answer there", "Listing as many effects as possible with no explanation of any of them", "Describing your own personal favourite piece of sports technology in far greater detail than needed", "A balanced look at both positive and negative effects, ending in a justified judgement"], "answer": 3, "explain": "The top band needs balance across both sides plus a judgement — a single effect, a bare list, or a personal favourite would all be capped much lower."}}, {"title": "Balance is everything — both sides, then a judgement", "html": "<p>The most common way to lose marks on this topic is writing about only positives, or only negatives. Build your answer as <strong>positive → negative → judgement</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>❌ weak:</strong> \"Technology is good because it shows replays.\" (one-sided, no negative, no judgement.)</li>\n<li><strong>✅ strong:</strong> \"Big screen replays help fans understand decisions, but the wait for a review can break the atmosphere. Overall, the benefit to understanding probably outweighs the loss of atmosphere for a big decision.\"</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Also weigh <strong>suitability</strong>: not every fixture needs, or can afford, the same level of technology as a major final.</p>", "check": {"question": "Why should you weigh up the ''suitability'' of technology in a longer answer on this topic?", "options": ["It shows you understand that not every fixture needs or can justify the same technology", "It proves that every single possible piece of technology should be used at every single match", "It removes any requirement to mention a single negative effect in your answer", "It replaces the need to reach any final judgement at the end of your answer"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Suitability shows deeper understanding — that the right amount of technology depends on the event — it does not mean ''use everything'', skip negatives, or avoid a judgement."}}, {"title": "Where this appears + sentence starters", "html": "<p><strong>Where it shows up:</strong> quick recall of positive/negative effects appears in <strong>Section A</strong>. Applied questions about a named stadium, club or event appear in <strong>Section B</strong>. The balanced 8-mark <strong>Discuss/Evaluate</strong> question in <strong>Section C</strong> often asks whether technology has \"improved\" the spectator experience overall.</p>\n<p><strong>Three punchy tips:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Always pair a positive with a genuine negative — examiners reward balance, not a one-sided list.</li>\n<li>Use the scenario''s own details (the stadium, the club, the ticket price) rather than a generic example.</li>\n<li>Finish with a judgement that says WHICH matters more and WHY, not just \"it depends\".</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Sentence starters for a longer answer:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\"One positive effect of technology here is… because…\"</li>\n<li>\"However, a negative effect is… because…\"</li>\n<li>\"Overall, I think technology has/has not improved the experience because…\"</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "Why is finishing a longer answer with a clear judgement important?", "options": ["Because a judgement lets you avoid mentioning any negative effects at all", "Because a judgement is only ever needed in Section A multiple-choice questions", "Because it shows which effect matters more and why, not just that both exist", "Because examiners only read the very first sentence of any longer answer"], "answer": 2, "explain": "A judgement shows you can weigh the effects and decide which matters more and why — simply listing both sides without deciding is not enough for the top band."}}]}, "exam": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "Identify <strong>one</strong> positive effect and <strong>one</strong> negative effect that technology can have on the spectator experience.", "marks": 2, "hint": "Give one genuine positive (e.g. replays aiding understanding, richer broadcasts) and one genuine negative (e.g. a long wait, cost, feeling less human).", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 2 marks (AO1)</h5>\n<p><strong>1 mark for a valid positive effect; 1 mark for a valid negative effect (must be a different effect from the positive).</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Positive effects include: big screen replays helping spectators follow/understand decisions; richer broadcast graphics and statistics; an enhanced experience for people watching from home.</li>\n<li>Negative effects include: long waits for a technology-based decision breaking the atmosphere; over-reliance on screens distracting from the live action; the cost of technology raising ticket or subscription prices; the experience feeling less \"human\".</li>\n</ul>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Which of these is a genuine negative effect of technology on the spectator experience?", "marks": 1, "hint": "Think about which option is a genuine, realistic downside rather than an exaggerated claim.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — A long wait for a video review can break the crowd''s atmosphere and tension.</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>This is a genuine negative effect: the delay interrupts the pace of the contest and quietens the crowd.</li>\n<li>The other options overstate what technology can do (guaranteeing correctness, removing the need to understand rules, or making enjoyment \"impossible\"), which is not accurate.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Explain how technology could both improve and reduce Priya''s experience of watching a match at Bramwell City''s stadium.", "marks": 4, "hint": "Give one way technology improves her experience in the stadium (e.g. understanding decisions) and one way it could reduce it (e.g. cost or a long wait), linked to the scenario.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 4 marks (AO2: application)</h5>\n<p><strong>Up to 2 marks for how technology improves Priya''s experience, up to 2 marks for how it could reduce it. 1 mark for identifying a relevant effect, 1 mark for linking it to Priya/the scenario.</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Improves:</strong> the big screen replay helps Priya understand a contested decision while she is at the stadium (positive effect applied to her attending in person).</li>\n<li><strong>Reduces:</strong> the paid live-stream subscription is an added cost for Priya, and/or a long video review during a match she attends could break the atmosphere she came to enjoy.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Accept any other reasonable, applied answer linked to the scenario.</p>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Discuss whether technology has improved the experience for spectators watching the cup final at Frameworth Arena.", "marks": 8, "hint": "Give positive effects (in the stadium and for broadcast/home viewers), negative effects (delay, distraction, cost, feeling less human), think about whether the technology is suitable for an event this big, then reach a judgement.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 8 marks (level-of-response). Read the band you fit, then pick a mark.</h5>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Band 3 (thorough), 6–8:</strong> a balanced discussion using both positive and negative effects, applied to the Frameworth Arena scenario, weighing the suitability of the technology for an event this size, ending in a justified judgement.</li>\n<li><strong>Band 2 (reasonable), 3–5:</strong> sound understanding of positive and/or negative effects with some application to the scenario, but the answer may be one-sided or the judgement unsupported.</li>\n<li><strong>Band 1 (basic), 1–2:</strong> names effects with little application and no real evaluation; largely a list.</li>\n<li><strong>0 marks:</strong> nothing creditworthy.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Indicative content (indicative, reward valid alternatives)</h5>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Positives:</strong> big screen replays help the crowd understand decisions; broadcast graphics/stats and extra camera angles deepen engagement for home viewers.</li>\n<li><strong>Negatives:</strong> a long review breaks the stadium atmosphere; spectators can over-rely on screens and miss live action; the cost of the technology is reflected in higher ticket prices; some fans feel it is less \"human\".</li>\n<li><strong>Suitability:</strong> a major final may justify expensive technology more than a small local fixture, because the importance of getting the decision right (and the size of the audience) is much greater.</li>\n<li><strong>Judgement:</strong> technology likely improves accuracy and depth of understanding, but this comes at a real cost to atmosphere and affordability, so the overall improvement depends on what a spectator values most.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>"}]}}'::jsonb),
('sport-studies', '6-1-command-words-and-exam-sections', '6.1 Command Words and Exam Sections', '{"learn": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "The R184 paper: three sections, one clock", "html": "<h4>The shape of the exam</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Unit R184 \"Contemporary issues in sport\" is assessed by a single <strong>written exam paper</strong>, worth <strong>70 marks</strong> in total, to be completed in <strong>1 hour 15 minutes</strong>.</li>\n<li>It is a <strong>terminal</strong> assessment — it must be sat in your final exam series, unlike the coursework units.</li>\n<li>The paper is split into <strong>three sections</strong>. Whatever the topic area, every section keeps testing the same skill: applying your knowledge and weighing things up, not just reciting facts.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Section A — 30 marks</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Mostly short recall: multiple-choice questions and shorter written answers (1–4 marks each).</li>\n<li>Section A also contains <strong>one longer, levelled question</strong> (worth 8 marks) that still needs a balanced, judged answer.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Section B — 28 marks</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Built around a <strong>context or scenario</strong> you are given — a named leisure centre, event, sport or performer that your answer must use.</li>\n<li>Mostly short-and-medium written answers, including <strong>levelled 6-mark questions</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Section C — 12 marks</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Also scenario-based, and built mainly around an <strong>extended response</strong>, including an <strong>8-mark \"Discuss\" or \"Evaluate\"</strong> question.</li>\n<li>Sections B and C always require analysis and evaluation — you cannot pass them by listing facts alone.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "Which of these correctly describes the R184 exam paper?", "options": ["70 marks in total, completed in 1 hour 15 minutes, split into three sections", "100 marks in total, completed in 2 hours, split into two sections", "50 marks in total, completed in 45 minutes, with no written answers at all", "70 marks in total, completed in 1 hour 15 minutes, made up only of multiple-choice questions"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The paper is 70 marks in 1 hour 15 minutes, across three sections (A/B/C) — not two, and not multiple-choice only."}}, {"title": "Command words: what the exam is really asking for", "html": "<h4>Same-looking questions, very different demands</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify / State</strong> — just name it. No explanation, no reason, no extra detail. One clear point usually earns one mark.</li>\n<li><strong>Describe</strong> — say what something is or what happens. More than naming it, but you are not yet giving a reason <em>why</em>.</li>\n<li><strong>Explain</strong> — give a reason. A safe habit is using the word <em>\"because\"</em> somewhere, linking a point to its cause or effect.</li>\n<li><strong>Discuss</strong> — present <strong>both sides</strong> of an issue. You do not have to pick a winner, but you must show understanding of more than one side.</li>\n<li><strong>Evaluate</strong> — go one step further than Discuss: weigh up both sides <em>and</em> reach a <strong>justified judgement</strong> about which matters most, or whether something is worth it overall.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Why the difference matters</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Writing an \"Explain\" style answer when the command word is \"State\" wastes time you need elsewhere on the paper.</li>\n<li>Writing a one-sided answer when the command word is \"Discuss\" or \"Evaluate\" caps your mark in a lower band, however well written that one side is.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "Which command word specifically asks you to reach a justified judgement, not just present both sides?", "options": ["Describe", "Evaluate", "Identify", "State"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Evaluate is the command word that demands a justified judgement; Discuss stops at weighing both sides; Identify/State/Describe don''t ask for any judgement."}}, {"title": "Reading the mark tariff to size your answer", "html": "<h4>The number in the brackets is an instruction</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>[1]</strong> — one point is enough. Writing three sentences to earn one mark steals time from later questions.</li>\n<li><strong>[2]</strong> — usually two separate points, or one point that is properly developed.</li>\n<li><strong>[4]</strong> — in Section B, this is usually points <strong>applied</strong> to the scenario you are given, not generic knowledge recited from memory. Two applied points, each worth two marks, is a common shape.</li>\n<li><strong>[6] / [8]</strong> — a <strong>levelled</strong> question. The mark scheme is banded, not a checklist: reaching the top band needs both sides of the issue <strong>and</strong> a justified judgement, applied to any scenario given.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Tariff mismatches are the easiest marks to lose</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A single unexplained word for an 8-mark question loses almost all the marks available, however correct that word is.</li>\n<li>A three-page answer to a 1-mark question still earns exactly one mark — the extra time spent writing it is wasted.</li>\n<li>Before you write, glance at the command word and the mark tariff together — they tell you the shape of answer the examiner expects.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "A question is worth [4] marks and is set in Section B, using a named scenario. What does this tariff most likely require?", "options": ["One single fact, stated with no further detail at all", "Points that are applied to the given scenario, not just generic knowledge", "Both sides of the argument fully weighed, ending in a justified judgement", "A single multiple-choice letter chosen with no working shown at all"], "answer": 1, "explain": "A [4]-mark Section B question usually wants points applied to the scenario — the full both-sides-plus-judgement shape belongs to a [6]/[8] levelled question instead."}}, {"title": "Putting it together across the whole R184 spec", "html": "<h4>The skill is the same wherever the content changes</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Command words and tariffs work exactly the same way whichever topic area a question is drawn from — participation, values, PEDs, hosting events, NGBs or technology.</li>\n<li><strong>\"Identify two user groups\" [2]</strong> — two names, nothing more.</li>\n<li><strong>\"Explain why a performer might use a PED\" [2]</strong> — a reason, using \"because\", not just naming a PED.</li>\n<li><strong>\"Describe how technology can support match officials\" [2]</strong> — say what the technology does (for example, checking a close decision), not why it matters.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Two more examples: a Governing Body, and technology for spectators</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>\"State two responsibilities of a named National Governing Body\" [2]</strong> — just name two, from rules and discipline, coaching, safety or funding. No explanation needed.</li>\n<li><strong>\"Evaluate whether increased use of technology has been good for spectators\" [8]</strong> — this needs both the positives (big screens, instant replays) and the negatives (cost, a slower flow of the game), ending in a justified overall view.</li>\n<li>Whatever the topic, ask yourself the same two questions before you write: <em>What does this command word want? What does this mark tariff give me time for?</em></li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "A question reads: ''Evaluate whether increased use of technology has been good for spectators.'' [8] What must a top-band answer include?", "options": ["Only the positive effects of technology on spectators, described in full detail with no negatives mentioned at all", "Both positive and negative effects on spectators, ending in a justified judgement", "A single named piece of technology, identified with no further comment", "Two separate user groups who might attend the event, simply named"], "answer": 1, "explain": "An 8-mark Evaluate question needs balance (both sides) plus a justified judgement — one-sided detail, a bare name, or an unrelated user-group list all miss what the command word demands."}}]}, "terms": {"enabled": true, "pairs": [{"term": "R184 paper", "definition": "70 marks, 1 hour 15 minutes, three sections (A/B/C), a terminal assessment"}, {"term": "Section A", "definition": "30 marks — short recall incl. MCQ, plus one 8-mark levelled question"}, {"term": "Section B", "definition": "28 marks — scenario-based short/medium answers, incl. levelled 6-mark questions"}, {"term": "Section C", "definition": "12 marks — scenario-based extended response, incl. an 8-mark Discuss/Evaluate"}, {"term": "Identify / State", "definition": "Just name it — no explanation needed"}, {"term": "Explain", "definition": "Give a reason — try using the word because"}, {"term": "Discuss", "definition": "Present and weigh up both sides of an issue"}, {"term": "Evaluate", "definition": "Weigh up both sides and reach a justified judgement"}]}, "mcq": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "How many marks is the whole R184 exam paper worth, and how long do you have to complete it?", "options": ["70 marks, to be completed in 1 hour and 15 minutes", "100 marks, to be completed in 2 hours and 30 minutes", "50 marks, to be completed in 45 minutes flat", "60 marks, to be completed in 1 hour and 30 minutes"], "answer": 0, "explain": "R184 is 70 marks in 1 hour 15 minutes. The other totals and times do not match the real paper."}, {"question": "Which of these correctly matches a section of the R184 paper to its marks and features?", "options": ["Section B is worth 28 marks and is always built around a scenario", "Section A is worth 30 marks and is always built around a scenario", "Section C is worth 12 marks and is entirely multiple choice with no writing", "Section A is worth 12 marks and is always built around a scenario"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Section B is 28 marks and scenario-based. Section A is 30 marks but is mostly short recall, not scenario-based; Section C is not entirely multiple choice."}, {"question": "A Section C question says: ''Evaluate whether the legacy of hosting a major event outweighs its cost.'' Which command word tells you to reach a justified judgement?", "options": ["Evaluate — because it specifically asks for a weighed, justified judgement", "Discuss — because it specifically asks for a weighed, justified judgement instead", "Identify — because naming the legacy is all that is required here", "Describe — because explaining what a legacy means is all that is required"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Evaluate demands a justified judgement. Discuss only asks you to weigh both sides without necessarily reaching one; Identify and Describe don''t ask for judgement at all."}, {"question": "A Section A question is worth [1] mark. What is the safest way to answer it?", "options": ["Give one short point, with no further explanation needed", "Write a fully developed paragraph explaining every possible reason", "Present both sides of the issue before reaching a judgement", "Leave the answer blank until you reach the higher-mark questions"], "answer": 0, "explain": "A [1]-mark question wants one clear point. A full paragraph, a both-sides discussion, or leaving it blank all waste marks or time."}, {"question": "Which pair correctly matches a command word to what it demands?", "options": ["Describe: say what something is or what happens", "State: weigh up both sides and reach a justified conclusion", "Explain: give a reason, often using the word because", "Discuss: simply name something with no further detail at all"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Explain = point plus reason (because). State actually means ''just name it''; Discuss actually means ''weigh both sides'' — this option has swapped their real meanings."}, {"question": "A Section B question is worth [4] marks and gives you a named scenario. What does this tariff most likely require?", "options": ["One single unexplained fact, worth all four marks alone", "Points applied to the given scenario, not just generic knowledge", "Both sides of an argument, fully weighed, ending in an overall judgement", "A multiple-choice letter chosen with no further working shown"], "answer": 1, "explain": "A [4]-mark Section B question wants points applied to the scenario. The full both-sides-plus-judgement shape belongs to a [6]/[8] levelled question, not a [4]-marker."}]}, "fib": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"text": "The whole R184 exam paper is worth [70] marks in total."}, {"text": "You have [75] minutes in total to complete the R184 exam paper."}, {"text": "Section [B] is worth 28 marks and is always built around a scenario."}, {"text": "Section [C] is worth 12 marks and includes an 8-mark Discuss or Evaluate question."}, {"text": "The command word that asks you to just name something, with no explanation, is [Identify] (or State)."}, {"text": "The command word that asks you to weigh up both sides AND reach a justified judgement is [Evaluate]."}]}, "tf": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"statement": "The R184 exam paper is worth 70 marks and lasts 1 hour 15 minutes.", "answer": true, "explain": "That''s the real total — 70 marks in 1 hour 15 minutes, across three sections."}, {"statement": "Section A contains only multiple-choice questions and nothing else.", "answer": false, "explain": "Section A also has shorter written answers and one longer, levelled 8-mark question — it isn''t all MCQ."}, {"statement": "Sections B and C are both built around a scenario or context you are given.", "answer": true, "explain": "Both sections give you a named scenario your answer must use, and both require analysis and evaluation."}, {"statement": "''Identify'' and ''Evaluate'' ask you for exactly the same kind of answer.", "answer": false, "explain": "Identify wants a bare name; Evaluate wants both sides weighed plus a justified judgement — very different demands."}, {"statement": "A [1]-mark question is best answered with a single, short point.", "answer": true, "explain": "One clear point secures the one available mark; anything longer just spends time you need elsewhere."}, {"statement": "Writing far more than a question''s mark tariff calls for always earns extra credit.", "answer": false, "explain": "Marks are capped at the tariff, so extra length beyond what is needed earns nothing extra and wastes time."}]}, "misc": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"myth": "If I write more for a 1-mark question, I can''t lose marks, so it''s safer to explain fully.", "truth": "Marks are capped at the tariff — a 1-mark question gives exactly 1 mark for a correct point, however much you write around it. The real cost is TIME: minutes spent over-explaining a 1-mark answer are minutes you don''t have left for a 6- or 8-mark question later in the paper.", "check": {"question": "Why is writing a long explanation for a 1-mark question a mistake?", "options": ["Because it cannot earn more than the 1 mark available, and wastes time needed elsewhere", "Because examiners deduct marks for writing any extra detail beyond what a question specifically asks for", "Because 1-mark questions never actually appear on the real R184 paper", "Because long answers are always factually incorrect by definition"], "answer": 0, "explain": "A 1-mark question is capped at 1 mark regardless of length — the real loss is the time taken away from higher-mark questions."}}, {"myth": "''Discuss'' means giving only the side of the argument I personally agree with, as long as I explain it well.", "truth": "''Discuss'' specifically means presenting BOTH sides, even if you personally think one is stronger. A brilliantly explained one-sided answer is capped in a lower band, because the mark scheme rewards balance before it rewards depth.", "check": {"question": "A student writes only the positive effects of hosting a major event for a ''Discuss'' question. What happens to their mark?", "options": ["It automatically scores full marks if the writing quality is excellent", "It is capped in a lower band, because Discuss requires both sides", "It scores zero, because one-sided answers are never credited at all", "It is marked the same as a 1-mark ''State'' question regardless of length"], "answer": 1, "explain": "A one-sided Discuss answer still earns some credit but is capped in a lower band — full marks need balance, not just polish."}}, {"myth": "Section B and Section C are basically the same, so it doesn''t matter which one I''m answering.", "truth": "They share the ''scenario-based'' feature, but carry different marks and demands: Section B is 28 marks of short-and-medium answers including 6-mark levelled questions; Section C is 12 marks built mainly around one 8-mark Discuss/Evaluate extended response. Knowing which section you are in helps you judge how much to write.", "check": {"question": "What is a genuine difference between Section B and Section C?", "options": ["Section B is 28 marks of short/medium answers; Section C is 12 marks centred on one extended response", "Section B never uses a scenario, but Section C always does", "Section C is worth more marks overall than both Section A and Section B combined, according to this claim", "Section B contains no written answers of any kind, only multiple choice"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Section B (28 marks, short/medium) and Section C (12 marks, one extended response) both use a scenario but differ in marks and shape."}}, {"myth": "The number of marks tells me how many separate facts to list — 8 marks means I should list 8 facts.", "truth": "A high tariff on a levelled question (6 or 8 marks) is NOT ''one mark per fact''. It is marked in bands: a thorough, balanced, judged answer can reach the top band with far fewer than 8 separate facts, while 8 disconnected facts with no balance or judgement stays stuck in a low band.", "check": {"question": "For an 8-mark ''Evaluate'' question, what actually reaches the top band?", "options": ["Listing exactly eight separate facts, regardless of whether they connect to each other", "A balanced answer covering both sides plus a justified judgement", "Naming eight different named examples with no further comment at all", "Repeating the same single point in eight slightly different sentences"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Levelled questions are marked by band, not by fact-count — balance plus a justified judgement is what reaches the top band."}}]}, "tips": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "Command words for this page — matching length to demand", "html": "<p>Every R184 question opens with a command word. Match your answer''s length and shape to it, not to the space left on the page:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify / State</strong> — one short point. Nothing more, however tempting.</li>\n<li><strong>Describe</strong> — say what it is or what happens; still no reason needed yet.</li>\n<li><strong>Explain</strong> — give a reason. A safe habit: use the word \"because\" somewhere.</li>\n<li><strong>Discuss / Evaluate</strong> — both sides, and for Evaluate, a justified judgement too.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Check the tariff too:</strong> [1] = one point; [4] = applied points; [6]/[8] = levelled and banded — never a simple checklist.</p>", "check": {"question": "A question says: ''Describe two ways technology supports match officials [2]''. What does ''Describe'' need here?", "options": ["Simply naming two pieces of technology, with no further detail at all", "Saying what each piece of technology does, not just naming it", "Explaining why officials need this kind of support in the first place", "Weighing up whether technology is good or bad for officiating overall"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Describe wants what the technology does — naming it alone (Identify) or explaining why/weighing it up (Explain/Evaluate) are different command words."}}, {"title": "The golden rule for Section B and C: use the scenario", "html": "<p>Sections B and C always give you a scenario — a named leisure centre, event, sport or performer. The most common way to lose marks here is writing a generally-true answer that ignores it.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>❌ generic:</strong> \"Hosting events can bring investment.\"</li>\n<li><strong>✅ applied:</strong> \"Hosting the event described brings investment, because the scenario mentions new transport links being built for it.\"</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Build applied answers as <strong>point → scenario detail → effect</strong>, whichever topic area the scenario is drawn from.</p>", "check": {"question": "In a Section B or C scenario question, where should your example come from?", "options": ["Any sport you personally follow, regardless of the scenario given", "The scenario you have actually been given in the question", "A generic textbook example that could apply to any scenario", "The mark scheme from a completely different exam paper"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Sections B and C are applied — marks are for using the given scenario. A generic example that ignores it is capped."}}, {"title": "Where this shows up + sentence starters for the levelled questions", "html": "<p><strong>Where the skill is tested:</strong> command-word discipline matters in every section, but the biggest marks ride on the levelled questions — one 8-marker in Section A, 6-markers in Section B, and the 8-mark Discuss/Evaluate that anchors Section C.</p>\n<p><strong>Three punchy tips:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Before writing anything, underline the command word and circle the mark tariff.</li>\n<li>For a levelled question, jot down both sides first — it stops your answer drifting one-sided.</li>\n<li>Finish every Discuss/Evaluate with one judgement sentence, even a short one — it is often worth real marks.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Sentence starters:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\"One argument in favour is… because…\"</li>\n<li>\"On the other hand… because…\"</li>\n<li>\"Overall, the most significant point is… because…\"</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "Why is finishing a Discuss/Evaluate answer with a judgement sentence worthwhile?", "options": ["It fills space at the end of the answer with no real benefit at all", "It is often where real marks sit, especially for Evaluate questions", "It replaces the need to give both sides of the argument beforehand", "It is only ever relevant for a 1-mark ''State'' question"], "answer": 1, "explain": "A justified concluding judgement is often exactly what separates a mid-band answer from a top-band one, especially for Evaluate."}}]}, "exam": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "State the total number of marks available on the R184 exam paper, and state the total time allowed to complete it.", "marks": 2, "hint": "Two separate facts — a number of marks, and an amount of time. No explanation is needed for either.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 2 marks (AO1)</h5>\n<p><strong>1 mark for the correct total marks; 1 mark for the correct total time:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>70 marks</li>\n<li>1 hour 15 minutes</li>\n</ul>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Which command word asks you to simply name something, with no explanation required?", "marks": 1, "hint": "Think about which word needs no reason and no judgement at all — just a name.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — Identify or State.</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Identify/State only requires naming something — no reason (Explain) and no judgement (Discuss/Evaluate).</li>\n</ul>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Explain how Priya should change her approach to each of these two questions so that her answers match what the command word and mark tariff actually require.", "marks": 4, "hint": "Take each question in turn. Say what she should do differently, and give a reason linked to the command word or the tariff.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 4 marks (AO2: application)</h5>\n<p><strong>Up to 2 marks per question: 1 for saying what Priya should do differently, 1 for a reason linked to the command word or tariff. Answers may include:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The 1-mark ''State'' question</strong> — Priya should give one short, unexplained point instead of a paragraph, because a 1-mark question is capped at one mark and the extra writing wastes time needed for later questions.</li>\n<li><strong>The 6-mark ''Discuss'' question</strong> — Priya should cover both the side she wrote and the opposing side, because Discuss requires balance, and a one-sided answer is capped in a lower band however well argued.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Accept any other reasonable, applied answer. A change with no reason, or a reason not linked to the command word/tariff, earns 1 of the 2 marks for that question.</p>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Discuss how understanding command words and mark tariffs can help a candidate score more marks in the R184 exam.", "marks": 8, "hint": "Cover more than one command word or tariff, drawing examples from across the spec. Show a benefit AND a limit, then finish with an overall judgement.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 8 marks (level-of-response). Read the band you fit, then pick a mark.</h5>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Band 3 (thorough), 6–8:</strong> a balanced discussion covering more than one command word and tariff, with examples drawn from across the R184 spec, clearly showing how correct technique secures marks AND weighing its limits, ending in a justified judgement.</li>\n<li><strong>Band 2 (reasonable), 3–5:</strong> sound understanding applied with some analysis, but the discussion may be one-sided or the judgement unsupported.</li>\n<li><strong>Band 1 (basic), 1–2:</strong> names command words and/or tariffs with little application and no real evaluation; largely a list.</li>\n<li><strong>0 marks:</strong> nothing creditworthy.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Indicative content (indicative, not a checklist — reward valid alternatives)</h5>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Recall questions:</strong> knowing that Identify/State needs only a bare point (e.g. naming user groups) stops candidates over-writing 1–2 mark answers and losing time.</li>\n<li><strong>Applied questions:</strong> knowing a [4]-mark Section B question wants points applied to the scenario, not generic knowledge (e.g. a named NGB''s specific responsibilities), earns marks that a generic answer would miss.</li>\n<li><strong>Levelled questions:</strong> recognising that a [6]/[8] question (e.g. an Evaluate on hosting a major event, or on PED sanctions) needs both sides plus a justified judgement, not a one-sided or list-like answer.</li>\n<li><strong>Evaluation:</strong> command-word technique only helps if the candidate has also learned the content — it cannot invent facts about WADA, technology or emerging sports that were never revised; technique amplifies knowledge, it does not replace it.</li>\n<li><strong>Judgement:</strong> understanding command words and tariffs is powerful because it converts existing knowledge into the marks actually available — but its benefit is capped by how much content the candidate has genuinely learned.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>"}]}}'::jsonb),
('sport-studies', '6-2-extended-response-technique', '6.2 Extended-Response Technique', '{"learn": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "The 3-step method for a top-band answer", "html": "<h4>Why facts alone are not enough</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>\"Discuss\" and \"Evaluate\" questions are never marked on facts alone. A page of accurate points, with no thinking done to them, still lands near the bottom of the mark range.</li>\n<li>Build every levelled answer with the same three steps, in order.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Step 1 — Apply</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Link your very first point to the scenario in front of you — a named event, place or situation — rather than a general point that could belong to any question.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Step 2 — Analyse both sides</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>For each point: state it, <strong>develop</strong> it (explain the effect), then ask <strong>\"so what?\"</strong> — what does this actually mean for the people or organisation in the scenario?</li>\n<li>Do this for <strong>one side</strong> of the issue, then do it again for the <strong>other side</strong>. Both sides must appear, or the analysis stays incomplete.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Step 3 — Reach a justified judgement</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Finish by saying <strong>which side matters more</strong>, or <strong>what it depends on</strong> — and give a reason drawn from your own analysis, not a new, unexplained point.</li>\n<li>A judgement is a decision. A sentence that only restates your points is a summary, not a judgement, and does not earn the same credit.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "In the 3-step method, what is the main job of the ''analyse'' step?", "options": ["Weighing up both sides of the issue and explaining the effect of each point in turn", "Naming the scenario you were given, with no further comment added to it", "Copying out extra facts about the topic that were not actually asked for anywhere in the question", "Writing a one-line summary of the question before you start your answer"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Analysis means developing a point on each side and explaining its effect — naming the scenario is ''apply'', and copying facts or summarising the question skips analysis altogether."}}, {"title": "The band structure — what actually moves you up a band", "html": "<h4>Three bands, one method</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Band 1 (basic, bottom marks):</strong> a short, one-sided answer that mostly lists points, with little or no link to the scenario.</li>\n<li><strong>Band 2 (reasonable, middle marks):</strong> sound understanding, applied to the scenario, with some analysis — but it may still lean to one side, or end without a judgement that is properly supported.</li>\n<li><strong>Band 3 (thorough, top marks):</strong> a balanced discussion of both sides, applied throughout, that reaches a judgement and explains why that judgement was reached.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>The two things that lift Band 2 into Band 3</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Add the other side.</strong> A Band 2 answer often only explores one side well; adding a developed point on the opposite side is usually the single biggest gain available.</li>\n<li><strong>Add a reasoned judgement.</strong> Not \"overall, both are important\" — instead, name which matters more <em>in this scenario</em>, or what it depends on, and say why.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>What band marks are NOT about</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>They are not about writing more words. A short, balanced, judged answer beats a long, one-sided list every time.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "A student''s answer explores one side well and applies it to the scenario, but never mentions the other side. Which band does this best fit?", "options": ["Band 1, because nothing at all in the answer is applied to the given scenario", "Band 3, because one side is thoroughly and fully explained in detail", "Band 2, because it is applied with some analysis but is not yet balanced", "No band, because an unbalanced answer earns zero marks regardless"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Applied, some analysis, but one-sided is the Band 2 pattern — Band 3 needs both sides plus a judgement, and an unbalanced answer still earns credit, just not full marks."}}, {"title": "Sentence scaffolds for building the answer", "html": "<p>Use a fixed set of starters so you never forget a step. Each starter has a job.</p>\n<h4>Starting a point (apply + develop)</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>\"One reason [X] matters here is…\"</strong> — states the point and links it to the scenario.</li>\n<li><strong>\"This means that…\"</strong> — forces the \"so what?\" development the mark scheme rewards.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Moving to the other side</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>\"On the other hand…\"</strong> — signals to the examiner (and to you) that you are now covering the opposite side, which is exactly what turns Band 2 into Band 3.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Reaching the judgement</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>\"Overall, the most important [factor] is… because…\"</strong> — names a decision and gives a reason, rather than just restating both sides.</li>\n<li><strong>\"This depends on…\"</strong> — a valid judgement when the honest answer is \"it varies\", as long as you say what it varies with.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "Why does the starter ''On the other hand…'' matter so much in a levelled answer?", "options": ["It makes the answer noticeably longer without changing its content in any way", "It signals the switch to the second side of the argument, which balance needs", "It replaces the need to reach any final judgement at the end", "It is only useful in Section A multiple-choice questions"], "answer": 1, "explain": "''On the other hand'' marks the point where you bring in the opposite side — the exact move that lifts a one-sided Band 2 answer towards Band 3."}}, {"title": "Classic failings that cap your mark", "html": "<h4>1. Being one-sided</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Only exploring the side you find easiest caps you in Band 2, however well that one side is written.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>2. Just listing</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Weak:</em> \"Technology helps officials. It also helps spectators. It is used in many sports.\" Three true facts, zero development — this is a list, not analysis.</li>\n<li><em>Stronger:</em> \"Technology helps officials by reviewing close decisions, which means fewer errors reach the final result and the sport is seen as fairer.\"</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>3. A conclusion that only summarises</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Weak:</em> \"So, in conclusion, there are advantages and disadvantages to this.\" That sentence makes no decision — it is a summary wearing a judgement''s clothing.</li>\n<li><em>Stronger:</em> \"Overall, the disadvantages matter more here because the cost involved would stop smaller clubs from ever using this technology.\"</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>4. Ignoring the scenario</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A general point about \"sport\" instead of the named event, team or situation in front of you loses the application marks, even if the point itself is accurate.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "A student ends an answer with: ''So overall, there are good points and bad points to this.'' What is the main problem?", "options": ["It uses the word ''overall'', which examiners never want to see in an answer", "It is too short to be read by the examiner marking the paper", "It summarises rather than judging — it makes no decision or reasoned call", "It should have been written in the very first sentence of the answer instead"], "answer": 2, "explain": "A real judgement decides something and gives a reason. Restating that there are ''good and bad points'' is a summary, not a judgement, and does not earn top-band credit."}}]}, "terms": {"enabled": true, "pairs": [{"term": "Apply", "definition": "Link a point to the named scenario you were given, not a general example"}, {"term": "Analyse", "definition": "Develop a point and explain its effect, on one side and then the other"}, {"term": "Justified judgement", "definition": "A decision on which side matters more (or what it depends on), with a reason"}, {"term": "Band 1", "definition": "1–2 marks: short, one-sided, mostly lists points, little application"}, {"term": "Band 2", "definition": "Middle marks: applied, some analysis, may stay one-sided or lack a supported judgement"}, {"term": "Band 3", "definition": "Top marks: balanced, applied discussion of both sides with a reasoned judgement"}, {"term": "Listing", "definition": "Stating several true points with no development of their effect"}, {"term": "Summary (not a judgement)", "definition": "Restating that both sides exist, without deciding which matters more"}]}, "mcq": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "Which of these best describes what a justified judgement adds to a levelled answer?", "options": ["A decision about which side matters more, or what it depends on, with a reason", "A restatement of the points already made, written in slightly different words", "An extra fact about the topic that has not been mentioned anywhere before", "A promise that the student has checked their spelling and punctuation carefully"], "answer": 0, "explain": "A judgement decides something and gives a reason drawn from the analysis — restating points, adding an unrelated fact, or mentioning spelling does not count as one."}, {"question": "A Band 2 answer applies one side well but never covers the opposite side. What single change is most likely to move it towards Band 3?", "options": ["Making the one side that is already covered even longer and more detailed than before", "Adding a developed point on the other side, then a reasoned judgement", "Repeating the same point using different, more advanced vocabulary", "Removing the link to the scenario so the answer reads more generally"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Band 3 needs balance and a judgement. Lengthening one side, repeating a point, or removing the scenario link does not add the missing balance."}, {"question": "Which sentence below is an example of ''just listing'' rather than analysis?", "options": ["Technology helps officials. It also helps spectators. It is used in lots of sports.", "Technology helps officials review close calls, which reduces errors in the final result.", "Technology gives an advantage to teams that can afford the most advanced equipment.", "Technology can slow the game down, which may reduce enjoyment for some spectators."], "answer": 0, "explain": "The first option states three separate facts with no ''so what?'' development. The others each explain an effect, which is what analysis needs."}, {"question": "In a Section B or C scenario question, where should your supporting example come from?", "options": ["Any sport you personally follow, regardless of what the question describes", "The scenario or case study printed on the question paper itself", "The most famous athlete you can remember from any competition", "A general example that could apply to almost any similar question"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Application marks are for using the scenario given, not a general or personal example — even a well-written general point is capped if it ignores the case study."}, {"question": "Why does a one-sided answer stay capped in Band 2, even if that one side is detailed and well explained?", "options": ["Because Band 3 needs the discussion to cover both sides before a judgement", "Because detailed answers are always penalised for going into too much depth", "Because only Section C questions are ever marked using bands at all", "Because one-sided answers are usually far too short to reach any band"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Depth on one side is not the same as balance. Band 3 specifically requires both sides to be covered, however well one side alone is written."}, {"question": "A student writes: ''So overall, there are advantages and disadvantages to hosting a major event.'' Why does this fail to earn full judgement marks?", "options": ["It mentions the specific name of the event, which should never appear anywhere in a conclusion", "It restates that both sides exist instead of deciding which matters more, and why", "It is placed at the end of the answer instead of somewhere in the middle", "It does not use the word ''overall'' in the correct grammatical position"], "answer": 1, "explain": "That sentence only confirms both sides exist — a real judgement names which side is stronger (or what it depends on) and gives a reason for that call."}]}, "fib": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"text": "The first step of a top-band answer is to [apply] your point to the scenario you have been given."}, {"text": "The second step is to analyse [both] sides of the issue, not just the side you find easiest."}, {"text": "The final step is to reach a justified [judgement] about which side matters more, or what it depends on."}, {"text": "An answer that only states true facts with no development of their effect is called [listing]."}, {"text": "In Section B and C, your example must come from the [scenario] you have been given, not a general one."}, {"text": "Band 3 needs a [balanced] discussion — covering both sides fairly before reaching a judgement."}]}, "tf": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"statement": "A Band 3 answer must cover both sides of the issue, not just the side you find easiest.", "answer": true, "explain": "Balance is one of the two things (with a reasoned judgement) that separates Band 3 from Band 2."}, {"statement": "As long as every sentence you write is a true fact, your answer is guaranteed to reach Band 3.", "answer": false, "explain": "A list of true, undeveloped facts stays in Band 1 — marks come from developing points and reaching a judgement, not from accuracy alone."}, {"statement": "A conclusion that only restates that ''there are advantages and disadvantages'' is the same as a justified judgement.", "answer": false, "explain": "That sentence is a summary. A real judgement decides which side matters more, or what it depends on, and gives a reason."}, {"statement": "In a Section B or C scenario question, your supporting example should come from the case study you were given.", "answer": true, "explain": "Application marks reward using the scenario in front of you — a general example, however accurate, is capped."}, {"statement": "Moving from Band 2 to Band 3 usually means adding the other side of the argument and a reasoned judgement.", "answer": true, "explain": "Those are the two changes most likely to lift a one-sided, applied answer into the top band."}, {"statement": "A one-sided answer can still reach Band 3 as long as that one side is written in great detail.", "answer": false, "explain": "Depth on one side does not replace balance. Band 3 specifically requires both sides to be covered before the judgement."}]}, "misc": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"myth": "If I write lots of accurate facts about the topic, I should get full marks.", "truth": "Accuracy is not the same as analysis. A list of true facts with no development (''technology helps officials, it also helps spectators, it is used in many sports'') stays in Band 1. Marks come from developing a point (''this means that…''), covering both sides, and reaching a judgement — not from the number of correct facts on the page.", "check": {"question": "A student writes five accurate, undeveloped facts about a topic. Which band does this best match?", "options": ["Band 3, because every fact stated is completely accurate and true", "Band 1, because listing facts with no development shows little analysis", "No band, because only inaccurate answers are ever marked this particular way", "Band 2, because five facts is usually considered enough for that band"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Accuracy alone is a Band 1 pattern. Reaching Band 2 or 3 needs development, application and — for the top band — balance and a judgement."}}, {"myth": "I only need to explain one side of the argument really well to get full marks.", "truth": "A single, well-developed side caps you in Band 2. Band 3 specifically asks for both sides — so plan two developed points, one for each side, before you reach your judgement. Depth on one side is valuable, but it cannot replace balance.", "check": {"question": "Why can''t a very detailed, one-sided answer reach the top band?", "options": ["Because detailed answers are penalised for taking too long to mark", "Because the top band specifically requires both sides to be covered", "Because one-sided answers must always contain at least one factual error", "Because only short answers are ever placed into the top band"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The top band''s descriptor requires balance across both sides, on top of depth — so one side alone, however detailed, is capped below it."}}, {"myth": "My conclusion just needs to sum up the points I already made.", "truth": "A summary restates; a judgement decides. Compare: ''So there are advantages and disadvantages'' (summary — no decision) with ''Overall, the disadvantages matter more here because the cost would stop smaller clubs using it'' (judgement — a decision, with a reason). Only the second earns top-band credit.", "check": {"question": "What is missing from the sentence ''So, overall, there are advantages and disadvantages to this''?", "options": ["It is missing a decision about which side matters more, and a reason why", "It is missing the specific word ''overall'', which has been left out completely", "It is missing a link to any user group affected by the topic", "It is missing a command word taken from the original question"], "answer": 0, "explain": "That sentence never decides anything — a judgement needs a call (which side, or what it depends on) plus a reason drawn from the analysis."}}, {"myth": "I can use any example I like in a scenario question — it doesn''t need to come from the case study.", "truth": "Section B and C questions give you a scenario so that you APPLY your knowledge to it. A general, unlinked example — even if accurate — loses the application marks. Always pull a name, place or detail from the case study into your first sentence on each point.", "check": {"question": "A scenario question names a specific stadium and event. What should your example use?", "options": ["A completely different, unrelated event that the student prefers instead", "Details from the named stadium and event given in the scenario", "The most famous stadium in the world, regardless of the question", "No example at all, since Section B never asks for application"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Application marks reward using the scenario you were actually given — swapping in an unrelated example, however well known, does not earn them."}}]}, "tips": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "Discuss vs Evaluate — what the marks actually demand", "html": "<p>Both command words trigger the same 3-step method (apply → analyse both sides → judgement), but read the exact wording of the question before you start:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Discuss</strong> — weigh up the issue from more than one angle; a supported judgement is still expected at the top band.</li>\n<li><strong>Evaluate</strong> — the word itself points more directly at the final judgement, so make sure your last paragraph clearly states a decision, not just a summary.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Mark-count signal:</strong> 6 and 8 marks are always level-of-response (banded) — there is no fixed list of \"correct\" points, only bands describing HOW WELL you argue and judge.</p>", "check": {"question": "What do both ''Discuss'' and ''Evaluate'' questions have in common at the top band?", "options": ["Neither one ever requires you to mention the scenario given at all", "Both expect both sides to be covered and a judgement to be reached", "Both are always worth exactly one mark each on the paper", "Neither one is ever marked using bands or level descriptors"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Whichever command word is used, 6/8-mark answers are levelled, and the top band always needs balance plus a justified judgement."}}, {"title": "Where levelled questions appear + how to plan first", "html": "<p><strong>Where they show up:</strong> Section A carries one 8-mark levelled question; Section B often includes a 6-mark levelled question inside a scenario; Section C''s extended response ends with an 8-mark Discuss/Evaluate.</p>\n<p><strong>Plan for 60 seconds before writing:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Jot ONE point for each side of the issue, linked to the scenario.</li>\n<li>Decide your judgement <em>before</em> you write the final paragraph, so your analysis builds towards it instead of surprising you at the end.</li>\n</ul>", "check": {"question": "Why is it useful to decide your judgement before writing the final paragraph?", "options": ["So the analysis in the middle of the answer can build towards it", "So you can avoid mentioning the scenario anywhere in your answer", "So the answer can be written without covering the opposite side at all", "So you never need to write a final paragraph at all"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Planning the judgement first means every earlier point can be chosen to support it, rather than bolting on a rushed decision at the end."}}, {"title": "Sentence starters + a worked mini-example", "html": "<p><strong>Starters to reuse in any topic:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\"One reason [X] matters here is… This means that…\"</li>\n<li>\"On the other hand…\"</li>\n<li>\"Overall, the most important [factor] is… because…\"</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Worked mini-example (technology in sport):</strong> \"One reason video review helps this event is that it corrects close refereeing decisions. This means that results are seen as fairer, which protects the competition''s reputation. On the other hand, reviewing decisions takes time, which can slow the game and frustrate spectators watching live. Overall, fairness matters more here because a wrong result damages trust in the sport for far longer than a short delay is remembered.\"</p>", "check": {"question": "In the worked mini-example, which phrase signals the move to the opposing side?", "options": ["\"One reason… matters here\"", "\"This means that…\"", "\"On the other hand…\"", "\"Overall, the most important…\""], "answer": 2, "explain": "\"On the other hand\" is the scaffold that switches the answer to the second side — the move that makes the discussion balanced."}}]}, "exam": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "State <strong>two</strong> things a Band 3 (top-band) Discuss/Evaluate answer must show that a Band 1 answer does not.", "marks": 2, "hint": "Think about what the band descriptors add as you move up — balance, application, analysis, or a supported judgement.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 2 marks (AO1)</h5>\n<p><strong>1 mark for each correct feature named, to a maximum of two. Accept any two DIFFERENT features from:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Covers both sides of the issue (balance)</li>\n<li>Applies points clearly to the scenario throughout</li>\n<li>Develops points with analysis (explains the effect), not just listing them</li>\n<li>Reaches a justified judgement, with a reason, rather than a summary</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Do not credit the same feature written twice in different words.</p>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Which command word most directly requires you to weigh up both sides of an issue and reach a supported decision?", "marks": 1, "hint": "Think about which command word points most directly at the final step of the 3-step method — the judgement.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — Evaluate.</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Evaluate points most directly at reaching a supported decision, though Discuss questions are marked the same way.</li>\n<li>Identify, Describe and State are all lower-tariff command words that do not require a judgement.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Explain <strong>two</strong> reasons why this sample answer would not reach Band 3, even though every sentence in it is accurate.", "marks": 4, "hint": "Look at what the answer does NOT do. Does it develop its points? Does it cover the other side? Does it reach a judgement?", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 4 marks (AO3: analysis)</h5>\n<p><strong>Up to 2 marks per reason: 1 for identifying a genuine failing, 1 for explaining why it stops the answer reaching Band 3. Answers may include:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>It lists points without developing them</strong> — each sentence states a fact but never explains its effect (\"so what?\"), so it shows little analysis.</li>\n<li><strong>It is one-sided</strong> — every sentence is positive; there is no mention of a drawback (e.g. slower play, cost), so it cannot be balanced.</li>\n<li><strong>It reaches no judgement</strong> — the answer ends without deciding whether the benefits outweigh any drawback, or what that would depend on.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Accept any two different, genuine failings. A failing identified with no explanation of its effect earns 1 of the 2 marks for that reason.</p>\n</div>"}, {"question": "Discuss the extent to which introducing technology like this has improved sport for spectators.", "marks": 8, "hint": "Cover a benefit (fairness, understanding decisions on the big screen) and a drawback (delays, cost) applied to Northgate Arena, then reach a judgement on which matters more, or what it depends on.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 8 marks (level-of-response). Read the band you fit, then pick a mark.</h5>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Band 3 (thorough), 6–8:</strong> a balanced, well-applied discussion of both the benefits and drawbacks for Northgate Arena''s spectators, with analysis of effect, ending in a justified judgement.</li>\n<li><strong>Band 2 (reasonable), 3–5:</strong> sound understanding applied to the scenario with some analysis, but the discussion may stay one-sided or the judgement may be unsupported.</li>\n<li><strong>Band 1 (basic), 1–2:</strong> names benefits and/or drawbacks with little application and no real judgement; largely a list.</li>\n<li><strong>0 marks:</strong> nothing creditworthy.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Indicative content (indicative, not a checklist — reward valid alternatives)</h5>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Benefits for spectators:</strong> the big screens let fans see replays of close calls, so they understand decisions instead of being confused by them; this can make the event feel fairer and more engaging to watch.</li>\n<li><strong>Drawbacks for spectators:</strong> reviews pause play, which can break the atmosphere and frustrate fans who came for a fast-moving occasion; the cost of the technology may be passed on through higher ticket prices, which can put off fans on lower incomes.</li>\n<li><strong>Evaluation:</strong> whether this is an improvement may depend on the type of fan (a fan who values accuracy over pace) and on whether prices rise enough to exclude some spectators altogether.</li>\n<li><strong>Judgement:</strong> the technology is likely an improvement for most spectators because it builds trust in decisions, but only while price rises stay small enough that ordinary fans are not priced out of attending.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>"}]}}'::jsonb)
on conflict (subject_slug, topic_slug) do update set
  page_name = excluded.page_name,
  sections = excluded.sections,
  updated_at = now();
